// Unit 33: Heimat
// Level: B2

const UNIT_33 =
{n:33,lang:"de",srcLang:"en",track:"v2",title:"Heimat",sub:"Wo das Herz ist",icon:"🏡",level:"B2.2",color:"#7B5EE8",lessons:[
{id:"deu_r33l1",title:"Abflug",icon:"\u2708\uFE0F",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Abflug",desc:"BER Airport. The same glass and steel from Unit 1, but everything has changed. Verumius walks through the terminal like someone who belongs. He passes the DB ticket machines he once feared. But today he is not arriving. He is leaving.",goals:["Enter the world of Heimat and belonging","Learn vocabulary for nostalgia, longing, and emotional connection","Begin exploring what home means"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Heimweh",src:"homesickness",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"Neuter noun. No plural.\n'Heim' (home) + 'Weh' (pain/ache).",example:"A: Hast du manchmal Heimweh?\nB: Ja, besonders abends. Dann vermisse ich alles.\nA: Was vermisst du am meisten?\nB: Das Heimweh kommt in Wellen. Mal stark, mal leise.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you sometimes have homesickness?\nB: Yes, especially in the evenings. Then I miss everything.\nA: What do you miss most?\nB: The homesickness comes in waves. Sometimes strong, sometimes quiet.",funFact:"'Heim' (home) + 'Weh' (pain/ache). Literally: home-ache. Swiss mercenaries in the 17th century were the first documented sufferers. Doctors called it a medical condition. German named it perfectly."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Sehnsucht",src:"deep longing, yearning",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Plural: die Sehnsuchte.\n'Sehnen' (to long) + 'Sucht' (seeking).",example:"A: Kennst du das Gefühl der Sehnsucht?\nB: Ja, die Sehnsucht nach der Heimat ist stark.\nA: Es ist mehr als Vermissen.\nB: Viel mehr. Sehnsucht tut weh und ist trotzdem schoen.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you know the feeling of longing?\nB: Yes, the longing for home is strong.\nA: It is more than missing.\nB: Much more. Longing hurts and is still beautiful.",funFact:"One of the most untranslatable German words. Not just wanting something, but aching for it. 'Sehnsucht nach der Heimat' is a core concept in German Romantic literature and philosophy."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Abschied",src:"farewell, departure",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Masculine noun. Plural: die Abschiede.\n'Abschied nehmen' = to say goodbye.",example:"A: Hast du Abschied genommen?\nB: Ja, der Abschied fiel mir schwer.\nA: Von wem war der Abschied am schwersten?\nB: Von Hildi. Sie hat geweint.",exampleSrc:"A: Did you say goodbye?\nB: Yes, the farewell was hard for me.\nA: Whose farewell was the hardest?\nB: Hildi's. She cried.",funFact:"Every German departure involves a proper Abschied. Leaving without saying goodbye is considered rude. The root 'abscheiden' means to separate, and 'Abschied nehmen' is the formal expression."},
{type:"fb",s:"Hast du Berlin Lebewohl gesagt? Ja, der {1} fiel mir schwer.",a:["Abschied"],opts:["Abschied","Neuanfang","Aufbruch","Umzug"],hint:"The masculine noun for farewell. From 'abscheiden' (to separate). Taking the farewell actively.",sSrc:"Did you say goodbye to Berlin? Yes, the farewell was hard for me."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Neuanfang",src:"a fresh start, a new beginning",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Masculine noun. Plural: die Neuanfaenge.\n'Neu' (new) + 'Anfang' (beginning).",example:"A: Hast du Angst vor dem Neuanfang?\nB: Nein, ich freue mich darauf.\nA: Jeder Neuanfang ist eine Chance.\nB: Genau. Einen Neuanfang wagen.",exampleSrc:"A: Are you afraid of the new beginning?\nB: No, I am looking forward to it.\nA: Every new beginning is a chance.\nB: Exactly. To dare a new beginning.",funFact:"Germany knows Neuanfaenge: 1945, 1990, personal reinventions. 'Einen Neuanfang wagen' (to dare a new beginning). The compound captures hope and courage in one word."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Kindheit",src:"childhood",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. No plural.\n'Kind' (child) + '-heit' (state of being).",example:"A: Erinnerst du dich an deine Kindheit?\nB: Ja, die Kindheit war glücklich.\nA: Was war das Beste an deiner Kindheit?\nB: Die Freiheit. Keine Sorgen, keine Pflichten.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you remember your childhood?\nB: Yes, childhood was happy.\nA: What was the best about your childhood?\nB: The freedom. No worries, no duties.",funFact:"'Kind' (child) + '-heit' (state of being). The -heit suffix creates abstract states: the state of being a child. 'Die glückliche Kindheit' is a universal longing across cultures."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Vergangenheit",src:"the past",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. No plural.\nAlso the grammatical term for past tense.",example:"A: Denkst du oft an die Vergangenheit?\nB: Manchmal. Aber ich lebe im Hier und Jetzt.\nA: Die Vergangenheit loslassen ist schwer.\nB: Ja, aber noetig. Man muss nach vorne schauen.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you often think about the past?\nB: Sometimes. But I live in the here and now.\nA: Letting go of the past is hard.\nB: Yes, but necessary. You have to look forward.",funFact:"'Vergangen' (past/gone) + '-heit.' The state of being gone. Also the grammatical term for past tense in German. 'Die Vergangenheit loslassen' (to let go of the past) is easier said than done."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Geborgenheit",src:"feeling of shelter, emotional safety",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. No plural.\nNearly untranslatable. Deeper than 'safety.'",example:"A: Was bedeutet Geborgenheit für dich?\nB: Wenn ich mich sicher und geliebt fühle.\nA: Wo findest du Geborgenheit?\nB: Bei meiner Familie. In meinem Zuhause.",exampleSrc:"A: What does Geborgenheit mean to you?\nB: When I feel safe and loved.\nA: Where do you find Geborgenheit?\nB: With my family. In my home.",funFact:"'Geborgen' (sheltered/safe) + '-heit.' Nearly untranslatable. Not just safety but emotional warmth and protection. A child in its mother's arms feels Geborgenheit. Adults search for it forever."},
{type:"mc",q:"Geborgenheit ist fast unuebersetzbar. Was beschreibt es am besten?",opts:["Finanzielle Sicherheit und pers\u00f6nlicher Wohlstand","Emotionale Waerme, Schutz und Geborgenheit","Physische Fitness und beste Gesundheit","Geographisches Wissen \u00fcber die Heimat"],ans:"Emotionale Waerme, Schutz und Geborgenheit",hint:"More than physical safety. A deeply felt state of warmth and protection. What a child feels in its mother's arms."}
]},
{id:"deu_r33l1b",title:"Abflug (Teil 2)",icon:"\u2708\uFE0F",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Abflug (continued)",desc:"Continue practicing the vocabulary from this topic.",goals:["Review and practice key words"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Verbundenheit",src:"connectedness, bond",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. No plural.\n'Verbunden' (connected) + '-heit.'",example:"A: Fuehlst du eine Verbundenheit mit Berlin?\nB: Ja, eine tiefe Verbundenheit.\nA: Woher kommt dieses Gefühl?\nB: Aus den Erfahrungen, den Menschen, den Erinnerungen.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you feel a connection with Berlin?\nB: Yes, a deep connection.\nA: Where does this feeling come from?\nB: From the experiences, the people, the memories.",funFact:"'Verbunden' (connected) + '-heit.' The state of being bound together. 'Tiefe Verbundenheit' (deep connection) describes the invisible threads between people and places."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Vertrautheit",src:"familiarity, intimacy",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. No plural.\n'Vertraut' (familiar/trusted) + '-heit.'",example:"A: Was ist Vertrautheit?\nB: Wenn etwas sich sofort richtig anfühlt.\nA: Eine Straße, ein Geruch, eine Stimme.\nB: Genau. Die Waerme des Bekannten.",exampleSrc:"A: What is familiarity?\nB: When something immediately feels right.\nA: A street, a smell, a voice.\nB: Exactly. The warmth of the known.",funFact:"'Vertraut' (familiar/trusted) + '-heit.' The warmth of the known. When a street, a smell, a voice feels immediately recognizable. The state of trusting deeply."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Wurzel",src:"root",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Plural: die Wurzeln.\nBotanical and metaphorical.",example:"A: Kennst du deine Wurzeln?\nB: Ja, meine Wurzeln liegen am Mittelmeer.\nA: Wurzeln geben Halt.\nB: Aber manchmal muss man neue Wurzeln schlagen.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you know your roots?\nB: Yes, my roots are by the Mediterranean.\nA: Roots give stability.\nB: But sometimes you have to put down new roots.",funFact:"Same Germanic root as English 'root.' 'Seine Wurzeln kennen' (to know your roots). Trees need roots, people need Wurzeln. 'Entwurzelt' (uprooted) describes losing them."},
{type:"teach",trg:"nostalgisch",src:"nostalgic",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Adjective. From Greek 'nostos' (return) + 'algos' (pain).\n'Ein nostalgischer Blick' (a nostalgic look).",example:"A: Fuehlst du dich nostalgisch?\nB: Ja, ein nostalgischer Blick zurück.\nA: Nostalgie kann schoen sein.\nB: Schoen und schmerzhaft zugleich.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you feel nostalgic?\nB: Yes, a nostalgic look back.\nA: Nostalgia can be beautiful.\nB: Beautiful and painful at the same time.",funFact:"The Greek roots 'nostos' (return home) + 'algos' (pain) mean exactly the same as Heimweh: home-pain. Both languages invented the same concept independently."},
{type:"teach",trg:"vertraut",src:"familiar, trusted",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Adjective. From 'vertrauen' (to trust).\n'Eine vertraute Stimme' (a familiar voice).",example:"A: Klingt diese Stimme vertraut?\nB: Ja, sehr vertraut. Ich kenne sie.\nA: Vertraute Orte geben Sicherheit.\nB: Deshalb fühlt sich Berlin wie Heimat an.",exampleSrc:"A: Does this voice sound familiar?\nB: Yes, very familiar. I know it.\nA: Familiar places give security.\nB: That is why Berlin feels like home.",funFact:"What you trust is what feels familiar. The root verb 'vertrauen' (to trust) reveals the connection: familiarity grows from trust. 'Vertraute Umgebung' (familiar surroundings) means safety."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"die Vertrautheit",src:"familiarity, intimacy"},{trg:"die Wurzel",src:"root"},{trg:"nostalgisch",src:"nostalgic"},{trg:"vertraut",src:"familiar, trusted"}]},
{type:"teach",trg:"unvergesslich",src:"unforgettable",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Adjective. 'Un-' (not) + 'vergesslich' (forgettable).\n'Ein unvergesslicher Moment.'",example:"A: War deine Zeit in Berlin unvergesslich?\nB: Absolut unvergesslich. Jeder Tag.\nA: Was war der unvergesslichste Moment?\nB: Der erste Tag. Und der letzte.",exampleSrc:"A: Was your time in Berlin unforgettable?\nB: Absolutely unforgettable. Every day.\nA: What was the most unforgettable moment?\nB: The first day. And the last.",funFact:"'Un-' (not) + 'vergesslich' (forgettable). What cannot be forgotten. The un- prefix makes it absolute: memory refuses to let go. 'Ein unvergessliches Erlebnis' is the highest praise."},
{type:"teach",trg:"melancholisch",src:"melancholic",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Adjective. From Greek 'melancholia' (black bile).\n'Eine melancholische Stimmung.'",example:"A: Warum bist du so melancholisch?\nB: Der Abschied macht mich melancholisch.\nA: Melancholie ist nicht Traurigkeit.\nB: Nein, es ist ein sanfterer Schmerz.",exampleSrc:"A: Why are you so melancholic?\nB: The farewell makes me melancholic.\nA: Melancholy is not sadness.\nB: No, it is a gentler pain.",funFact:"The ancient Greeks believed this sweet, contemplative sadness came from black bile ('melancholia'). German adopted the word for that gentle ache that is not despair but something more beautiful."},
{type:"teach",trg:"vermissen",src:"to miss (someone/something)",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Regular verb. Not separable.\n'Ich vermisse Berlin' (I miss Berlin).",example:"A: Vermisst du Berlin?\nB: Ja, ich vermisse die Stadt sehr.\nA: Was vermisst du am meisten?\nB: Die Menschen. Die Nachbarschaft. Den Alltag.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you miss Berlin?\nB: Yes, I miss the city very much.\nA: What do you miss most?\nB: The people. The neighborhood. The daily life.",funFact:"'Ver-' + 'missen' (to miss). Not separable. The ver- prefix intensifies the absence. You do not just notice something missing. You feel the gap it left behind."},
{type:"fb",s:"War deine Zeit in Berlin {1}? Absolut. Jeder Tag war besonders.",a:["unvergesslich"],opts:["melancholisch","nostalgisch","unvergesslich","vertraut"],hint:"The adjective meaning unforgettable. Un- (not) + vergesslich (forgettable). Memory refuses to let go.",sSrc:"Was your time in Berlin unforgettable? Absolutely. Every day was special."},
{type:"teach",trg:"empfinden",src:"to feel, to sense",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Strong verb: empfinden / empfand / empfunden.\nDeeper than 'fühlen': emotional finding.",example:"A: Was empfindest du gerade?\nB: Ich empfinde Sehnsucht und Dankbarkeit.\nA: Beides gleichzeitig?\nB: Ja. Man kann beides empfinden.",exampleSrc:"A: What do you feel right now?\nB: I feel longing and gratitude.\nA: Both at the same time?\nB: Yes. You can feel both.",funFact:"'Emp-' (in) + 'finden' (to find). Finding something within yourself. Deeper than fühlen: empfinden is emotional discovery. Strong verb: empfinden / empfand / empfunden."},
{type:"teach",trg:"erinnern",src:"to remember",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Regular verb. Reflexive: 'sich erinnern an + Akk.'\n'Sich an die Kindheit erinnern.'",example:"A: Erinnerst du dich an den ersten Tag?\nB: Ja, ich erinnere mich genau daran.\nA: Manche Erinnerungen verblassen nie.\nB: Die wichtigen bleiben für immer.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you remember the first day?\nB: Yes, I remember it exactly.\nA: Some memories never fade.\nB: The important ones stay forever.",funFact:"'Er-' + 'inner' (inner). You bring something back into your inner self. Making the past internal again. Reflexive with an + Akkusativ: 'Ich erinnere mich an den Tag.'"},
{type:"teach",trg:"sehnen",src:"to yearn, to long",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Regular verb. Always reflexive: 'sich sehnen nach + Dat.'\n'Sich nach der Heimat sehnen.'",example:"A: Sehnst du dich nach der Heimat?\nB: Ja, ich sehne mich nach dem Meer.\nA: Sehnsucht ist ein deutsches Wort.\nB: Und ein deutsches Gefühl.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you long for home?\nB: Yes, I long for the sea.\nA: Sehnsucht is a German word.\nB: And a German feeling.",funFact:"The verb behind Sehnsucht. Always reflexive with nach. 'Sich nach der Heimat sehnen' (to long for home). A deep, slow ache that does not go away. The most German of emotions."},
{type:"mc",q:"Verumius fühlt Heimweh am Flughafen. Was bedeutet 'Heimweh' wörtlich?",opts:["Heim-Reise (trip home)","Heim-Suche (search for home)","Heim-Bau","Heim-Schmerz"],ans:"Heim-Schmerz",hint:"The compound breaks into two parts: a word for 'home' and a word for 'pain.' The literal translation is the answer."},
{type:"mc",q:"Geborgenheit ist fast unübersetzbar. Es beschreibt am besten...",opts:["das Gefühl, beschützt und emotional sicher zu sein","körperliche Fitness, Kraft und sportliche Ausdauer","finanzielle Stabilität, Sicherheit und persönlicher Wohlstand","geographisches Wissen über bekannte Heimatregionen und Orte"],ans:"das Gefühl, beschützt und emotional sicher zu sein",hint:"More than physical safety. A deeply felt state of warmth and shelter. Hard to translate directly into English."},
{type:"fb",s:"Ich {1} mich nach meiner Kindheit.",a:["sehne"],opts:["finde","sehne","denke","gehe"],hint:"The verb describes a deep ache for something absent. It is reflexive and pairs with 'nach'. Think of the noun 'Sehnsucht.'",sSrc:"I long for my childhood."},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'die Wurzel'?",opts:["to feel, to sense","root","feeling of shelter, emotional safety","homesickness"],ans:"root",hint:"A feminine noun. Trees have them. Metaphorically: your origins and connections."},
{type:"fb",s:"Wie sagt man 'to miss (someone/something)' auf Deutsch? {1}",a:["vermissen"],opts:["vermissen","die Kindheit","das Heimweh","die Verbundenheit"],hint:"ver- + missen (to miss). The ache of absence when someone or something is gone.",sSrc:"How do you say 'to miss (someone/something)' in German?"},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'erinnern'?",opts:["a fresh start, a new beginning","melancholic","to remember","to miss (someone/something)"],ans:"to remember",hint:"From inne (inner). To bring something from the inner past back to the present."}
]},
{id:"deu_r33l2",title:"Zwischen hier und dort",icon:"\uD83C\uDF0D",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Zwischen hier und dort",desc:"Between here and there. Between the place you came from and the place you live now. This lesson builds the vocabulary for places, memories, and belonging.",goals:["Build vocabulary for places, memories, and belonging","Understand the emotional geography of home","Describe what makes a place feel like Heimat"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Fernweh",src:"wanderlust, longing for distant places",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"Neuter noun. No plural.\n'Fern' (far) + 'Weh' (ache). The opposite of Heimweh.",example:"A: Hast du Fernweh?\nB: Ja, ich möchte die Welt sehen.\nA: Fernweh ist das Gegenteil von Heimweh.\nB: Man sehnt sich nach Orten, die man nie gesehen hat.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you have wanderlust?\nB: Yes, I want to see the world.\nA: Fernweh is the opposite of homesickness.\nB: You long for places you have never seen.",funFact:"'Fern' (far/distant) + 'Weh' (ache). The opposite of Heimweh. Not homesickness but 'farsickness.' Only German has a single word for the ache of wanting to be somewhere far away."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Nostalgie",src:"nostalgia",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. No plural.\nFrom Greek 'nostos' (return) + 'algos' (pain).",example:"A: Ist Nostalgie ein positives Gefühl?\nB: Ja und nein. Sie ist bittersüßs.\nA: Die Nostalgie lässt uns lächeln und weinen.\nB: Gleichzeitig. Das ist ihre Kraft.",exampleSrc:"A: Is nostalgia a positive feeling?\nB: Yes and no. It is bittersweet.\nA: Nostalgia makes us smile and cry.\nB: At the same time. That is its power.",funFact:"Same roots as 'nostalgisch.' Originally a medical diagnosis for Swiss soldiers missing home. Now: the bittersweet pleasure of remembering what once was."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Nachbarschaft",src:"neighborhood",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Plural: die Nachbarschaften.\n'Nachbar' (neighbor) + '-schaft' (collective).",example:"A: Magst du deine Nachbarschaft?\nB: Ja, die Nachbarschaft ist sehr freundlich.\nA: Gute Nachbarschaft ist wichtig.\nB: Sie macht einen Ort zur Heimat.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you like your neighborhood?\nB: Yes, the neighborhood is very friendly.\nA: Good neighborliness is important.\nB: It makes a place feel like home.",funFact:"'Nachbar' (neighbor) + '-schaft' (collective). 'Gute Nachbarschaft' (good neighborliness) is a German virtue. Your Nachbarschaft defines your daily Heimat more than your country does."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Landschaft",src:"landscape",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Plural: die Landschaften.\n'Land' (land) + '-schaft.'",example:"A: Wie ist die Landschaft in Norddeutschland?\nB: Flach und gruen. Ganz anders als im Sueden.\nA: Jede Landschaft hat ihren Charakter.\nB: Die deutsche Landschaft ist sehr vielfaeltig.",exampleSrc:"A: What is the landscape like in Northern Germany?\nB: Flat and green. Completely different from the south.\nA: Every landscape has its character.\nB: The German landscape is very diverse.",funFact:"'Land' (land) + '-schaft.' Caspar David Friedrich painted Germany's Romantic Landschaften. The word also means 'region' in political history. From North Sea to Alps, one word covers it all."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Atmosphäre",src:"atmosphere",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Plural: die Atmosphären.\nBoth literal (air) and figurative (mood).",example:"A: Die Atmosphäre in diesem Cafe ist toll.\nB: Ja, warm und einladend.\nA: Atmosphäre macht einen Ort besonders.\nB: Es ist das, was man fühlt, nicht sieht.",exampleSrc:"A: The atmosphere in this cafe is great.\nB: Yes, warm and inviting.\nA: Atmosphere makes a place special.\nB: It is what you feel, not what you see.",funFact:"Both literal (the air around Earth) and figurative (the mood of a place). Greek roots: 'atmos' (vapor) + 'sphaira' (sphere). 'Die Atmosphaere dieses Ortes' captures what makes a place feel alive."},
{type:"mc",q:"Was ist der Unterschied zwischen Landschaft und Nachbarschaft?",opts:["Beide Woerter bedeuten genau dasselbe","Landschaft ist menschlich, Nachbarschaft ist nat\u00fcrlich","Nachbarschaft ist ein Synonym f\u00fcr Atmosph\u00e4re","Landschaft beschreibt die Natur, Nachbarschaft die Gemeinschaft um dich herum"],ans:"Landschaft beschreibt die Natur, Nachbarschaft die Gemeinschaft um dich herum",hint:"Land + -schaft describes terrain and geography. Nachbar + -schaft describes the community of people who live near you."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Umgebung",src:"surroundings, environment",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Plural: die Umgebungen.\n'Um' (around) + 'Gebung' (surrounding).",example:"A: Kennst du die Umgebung?\nB: Ja, die nähere Umgebung ist mir vertraut.\nA: Die Umgebung praegt das Lebensgefühl.\nB: Man wird Teil seiner Umgebung.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you know the surroundings?\nB: Yes, the immediate surroundings are familiar to me.\nA: The surroundings shape one's feeling of life.\nB: You become part of your surroundings.",funFact:"'Um' (around) + 'Gebung' (giving/surrounding). What gives itself around you. Your physical context. 'Die nähere Umgebung' (the immediate surroundings) is what you see every day."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Andenken",src:"souvenir, memento",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"Neuter noun. Plural: die Andenken.\n'An' (at) + 'Denken' (thinking).",example:"A: Hast du ein Andenken aus Berlin?\nB: Ja, ein kleines Stück Berliner Mauer.\nA: Ein Andenken trägt Erinnerungen.\nB: Jedes Andenken erzählt eine Geschichte.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you have a souvenir from Berlin?\nB: Yes, a small piece of the Berlin Wall.\nA: A memento carries memories.\nB: Every souvenir tells a story.",funFact:"'An' (at) + 'Denken' (thinking). Thinking back at something. A physical object that carries memory. 'Ein Andenken an die Heimat' (a memento of home)."},
{type:"fb",s:"Die {1} in der Fremde kommt besonders abends, wenn man allein ist.",a:["Einsamkeit"],opts:["Einsamkeit","Landschaft","Atmosph\u00e4re","Vorfreude"],hint:"The feminine noun for loneliness or solitude. Einsam (lonely) + -keit. Not always negative: chosen solitude can be peaceful.",sSrc:"The loneliness abroad comes especially in the evenings, when one is alone."}
]},
{id:"deu_r33l2b",title:"Zwischen hier und dort (Teil 2)",icon:"\uD83C\uDF0D",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Zwischen hier und dort (continued)",desc:"Continue practicing the vocabulary from this topic.",goals:["Review and practice key words"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Praegung",src:"imprint, formative influence",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Plural: die Praegungen.\n'Praegen' (to stamp/shape) + '-ung.'",example:"A: Was ist kulturelle Praegung?\nB: Was dich in der Kindheit geformt hat.\nA: Praegung passiert früh.\nB: Und bleibt für immer. Sie macht dich, wer du bist.",exampleSrc:"A: What is cultural imprinting?\nB: What shaped you during childhood.\nA: Imprinting happens early.\nB: And stays forever. It makes you who you are.",funFact:"'Praegen' (to stamp/shape) + '-ung.' What got stamped into you during childhood. Konrad Lorenz studied Praegung in geese: the first thing they see, they follow. Humans have Praegung too."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Einsamkeit",src:"loneliness, solitude",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. No plural.\n'Einsam' (lonely) + '-keit.'",example:"A: Fuehlst du Einsamkeit in der Fremde?\nB: Manchmal. Einsamkeit kommt abends.\nA: Einsamkeit kann auch positiv sein.\nB: Stimmt. Gewaehlte Einsamkeit ist Ruhe.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you feel loneliness abroad?\nB: Sometimes. Loneliness comes in the evenings.\nA: Loneliness can also be positive.\nB: True. Chosen loneliness is peace.",funFact:"'Einsam' (lonely) + '-keit.' 'Die Einsamkeit der Fremde' (the loneliness of being abroad). Einsamkeit can be negative (loneliness) or positive (solitude). Context and choice decide."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Entfremdung",src:"alienation, estrangement",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. No plural.\n'Ent-' (away from) + 'Fremd' (foreign) + '-ung.'",example:"A: Was ist Entfremdung?\nB: Wenn die Heimat fremd wird.\nA: Man kommt zurück und erkennt nichts wieder.\nB: Entfremdung ist schmerzhaft. Du gehoerst nicht mehr dazu.",exampleSrc:"A: What is alienation?\nB: When home becomes foreign.\nA: You come back and recognize nothing.\nB: Alienation is painful. You no longer belong.",funFact:"'Ent-' (away from) + 'Fremd' (foreign) + '-ung.' Becoming foreign to what was once familiar. Marx used Entfremdung for workers alienated from their labor. Personally: when home no longer feels like home."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Lebensgefühl",src:"general sense of life, life feeling",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"Neuter noun. Plural: die Lebensgefühle.\n'Lebens' (life's) + 'Gefühl' (feeling). Fugen-s.",example:"A: Was ist das Berliner Lebensgefühl?\nB: Freiheit, Offenheit, Kreativitaet.\nA: Jede Stadt hat ihr eigenes Lebensgefühl.\nB: Und es verändert sich mit den Jahren.",exampleSrc:"A: What is the Berlin life feeling?\nB: Freedom, openness, creativity.\nA: Every city has its own life feeling.\nB: And it changes over the years.",funFact:"Nearly untranslatable. The overall emotional quality of your existence. 'Das Berliner Lebensgefühl' (the Berlin vibe). The Fugen-s links Leben to Gefühl in this compound."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Lebensphase",src:"life phase, stage of life",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Plural: die Lebensphasen.\n'Lebens' (life's) + 'Phase.' Fugen-s.",example:"A: In welcher Lebensphase bist du?\nB: Ich bin in einer Phase des Neuanfangs.\nA: Jede Lebensphase bringt neue Fragen.\nB: Und neue Antworten. Das ist das Schoene.",exampleSrc:"A: What life phase are you in?\nB: I am in a phase of new beginnings.\nA: Every life phase brings new questions.\nB: And new answers. That is the beauty of it.",funFact:"'Lebens' (life's) + 'Phase.' Kindheit, Jugend, Erwachsenenalter, Alter: each a Lebensphase. The Fugen-s connects the compound. German names every stage of life."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"die Einsamkeit",src:"loneliness, solitude"},{trg:"die Entfremdung",src:"alienation, estrangement"},{trg:"das Lebensgefühl",src:"general sense of life, life feeling"},{trg:"die Lebensphase",src:"life phase, stage of life"}]},
{type:"teach",trg:"bodenständig",src:"down-to-earth, grounded",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Adjective. 'Boden' (ground) + 'ständig' (standing).\n'Ein bodenständiger Mensch.'",example:"A: Bist du ein bodenständiger Mensch?\nB: Ja, ich bleibe gern auf dem Boden der Tatsachen.\nA: Bodenständig ist ein Kompliment.\nB: Es bedeutet: echt, ehrlich, nicht abgehoben.",exampleSrc:"A: Are you a down-to-earth person?\nB: Yes, I like to stay grounded in reality.\nA: Down-to-earth is a compliment.\nB: It means: real, honest, not pretentious.",funFact:"'Boden' (ground) + 'ständig' (standing). Standing firmly on the ground. Not pretentious. Connected to the earth and to reality. The highest compliment in rural Germany."},
{type:"teach",trg:"einheimisch",src:"local, native",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Adjective. 'Ein' (in) + 'heimisch' (homely).\n'Die einheimische Bevoelkerung.'",example:"A: Bist du einheimisch?\nB: Nein, ich bin zugezogen.\nA: Die Einheimischen kennen die besten Orte.\nB: Das stimmt. Sie wissen, wo es sich lohnt.",exampleSrc:"A: Are you a local?\nB: No, I moved here.\nA: The locals know the best places.\nB: That is true. They know where it is worth going.",funFact:"'Ein' (in) + 'heimisch' (homely). Those who are at home here. The opposite of fremd. Being einheimisch means this is your Heim. Used as noun: 'die Einheimischen' (the locals)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"heimatverbunden",src:"attached to one's homeland",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Adjective. 'Heimat' (home) + 'verbunden' (connected).\n'Ein heimatverbundener Mensch.'",example:"A: Bist du heimatverbunden?\nB: Ja, sehr. Meine Wurzeln sind wichtig.\nA: Heimatverbunden zu sein ist keine Schwaeche.\nB: Im Gegenteil. Es gibt Kraft.",exampleSrc:"A: Are you attached to your homeland?\nB: Yes, very much. My roots are important.\nA: Being attached to your homeland is not a weakness.\nB: On the contrary. It gives strength.",funFact:"'Heimat' (home) + 'verbunden' (connected). Connected by invisible bonds to the place that shaped you. A compound adjective that captures loyalty to origin."},
{type:"teach",trg:"praegend",src:"formative, shaping",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Present participle of 'praegen.'\n'Ein praegendes Erlebnis' (a formative experience).",example:"A: War Berlin eine praegende Erfahrung?\nB: Absolut. Die praegendste meines Lebens.\nA: Praegende Erlebnisse verändern uns.\nB: Sie formen, wer wir werden.",exampleSrc:"A: Was Berlin a formative experience?\nB: Absolutely. The most formative of my life.\nA: Formative experiences change us.\nB: They shape who we become.",funFact:"Present participle of 'praegen.' Something that stamps itself into you. 'Die praegenden Jahre' (the formative years). What marks you permanently."},
{type:"mc",q:"Er ist heimatverbunden. Was bedeutet das?",opts:["Er hat kein Zuhause und sucht eines","Er ist eng mit seiner Heimat verbunden","Er lebt weit entfernt von seiner Familie","Er interessiert sich nicht f\u00fcr seine Herkunft"],ans:"Er ist eng mit seiner Heimat verbunden",hint:"Describes someone with deep, invisible ties to the place they grew up in. Not physical closeness, but emotional belonging."},
{type:"teach",trg:"heimatlos",src:"homeless (having no homeland)",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Adjective. 'Heimat' + '-los' (without).\nNot 'obdachlos' (without shelter). Deeper.",example:"A: Fuehlst du dich manchmal heimatlos?\nB: Ja, zwischen zwei Welten. Nirgends ganz zu Hause.\nA: Heimatlos ist ein schweres Gefühl.\nB: Aber vielleicht kann man mehrere Heimaten haben.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you sometimes feel without a homeland?\nB: Yes, between two worlds. Nowhere fully at home.\nA: Being without a homeland is a heavy feeling.\nB: But perhaps you can have multiple homelands.",funFact:"'Heimat' + '-los' (without). Not 'obdachlos' (without shelter). Heimatlos is deeper: having no place that feels like home. Stateless refugees are heimatlos. It describes the soul, not the roof."},
{type:"teach",trg:"sesshaft",src:"settled, sedentary",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Adjective. From 'sitzen' (to sit) + '-haft' (stuck).\n'Sesshaft werden' (to settle down).",example:"A: Bist du sesshaft geworden?\nB: Ja, nach zehn Jahren Wandern bin ich sesshaft.\nA: Sesshaft werden ist eine Entscheidung.\nB: Die schwerste und die beste meines Lebens.",exampleSrc:"A: Have you settled down?\nB: Yes, after ten years of wandering I have settled down.\nA: Settling down is a decision.\nB: The hardest and the best of my life.",funFact:"Literally 'stuck sitting,' from 'sitzen' (to sit) + '-haft' (attached). When ancient nomads stopped moving, they became sesshaft. 'Sesshaft werden' still means to settle down today."},
{type:"mc",q:"Heimweh ist die Sehnsucht nach Hause. Was ist Fernweh?",opts:["die Angst vor weiten Reisen","die Angst vor dem Zuhause zu Hause","die Sehnsucht nach fernen Orten","die Zufriedenheit mit dem Zuhause"],ans:"die Sehnsucht nach fernen Orten",hint:"The opposite of Heimweh. 'Fern' (far away) + 'Weh' (pain). The pain for distant places."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"Geborgenheit",src:"feeling of shelter/safety"},{trg:"Entfremdung",src:"alienation"},{trg:"Einsamkeit",src:"loneliness/solitude"},{trg:"Sehnsucht",src:"deep longing"}]},
{type:"fb",s:"Seitdem ich in Berlin lebe, hat sich mein {1} verändert.",a:["Lebensgefühl"],opts:["Lebensgefühl","Fernweh","Abschied","Andenken"],hint:"Your general sense of life. The emotional quality of your existence.",sSrc:"Since I have been living in Berlin, my sense of life has changed."},
{type:"mc",q:"Im Wort 'Lebensgefühl' verbindet das -s- zwischen 'Leben' und 'Gefühl'...",opts:["eine Genitivmarkierung","eine Pluralendung","ein Fugenelement","eine Rechtschreibregel"],ans:"ein Fugenelement",hint:"The phonetic linking element in compound nouns. Leben-s-Gefühl."},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'die Praegung'?",opts:["imprint, formative influence","atmosphere","surroundings, environment","nostalgia"],ans:"imprint, formative influence",hint:"From prägen (to stamp/mint coins). The lasting mark that experiences leave on you."},
{type:"fb",s:"Bist du ein {1}er Mensch?",a:["bodenständig"],opts:["die Lebensphase","die Landschaft","bodenständig","praegend"],hint:"Boden (ground) + ständig (standing). Feet firmly on the ground. Practical, unpretentious.",sSrc:"Are you a down-to-earth person?"},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'einheimisch'?",opts:["local, native","life phase, stage of life","wanderlust, longing for distant places","nostalgia"],ans:"local, native",hint:"ein- (in) + heimisch (home-like). Belonging to this place originally. An original resident."},
{type:"fb",s:"War Berlin eine {1}e Erfahrung?",a:["praegend"],opts:["das Fernweh","die Nachbarschaft","die Nostalgie","praegend"],hint:"From prägen (to stamp/shape). An experience that shapes who you become.",sSrc:"Was Berlin a formative experience?"},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'sesshaft'?",opts:["loneliness, solitude","wanderlust, longing for distant places","nostalgia","settled, sedentary"],ans:"settled, sedentary",hint:"From sitzen/Sitz (to sit/seat) + -haft (attached to). Rooted in one place, no longer nomadic."}
]},
{id:"deu_r33l3",title:"Nachdem ich weggegangen war",icon:"\u23F3",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Nachdem ich weggegangen war",desc:"Verumius is at his Mediterranean family home. The kitchen smells the same. The light falls through the shutters the same way. But he catches himself thinking in German. Something has shifted.",goals:["Master advanced temporal clauses for complex time narration","Narrate life changes with before/after/during precision","Express the emotional timeline of leaving and returning"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Rückkehr",src:"return, homecoming",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. No plural in common use.\n'Rueck' (back) + 'Kehr' (turn).",example:"A: Wie war die Rückkehr?\nB: Seltsam. Alles ist gleich, aber ich bin anders.\nA: Die Rückkehr in die Heimat ist nie einfach.\nB: Nein. Man kehrt als ein anderer Mensch zurück.",exampleSrc:"A: How was the return?\nB: Strange. Everything is the same, but I am different.\nA: The return to the homeland is never easy.\nB: No. You return as a different person.",funFact:"'Rueck' (back) + 'Kehr' (turn). You turn back toward where you came from. Every Odyssey ends with a Rückkehr. The word itself mirrors the journey: going back."},
{type:"fb",s:"Wie war die {1}? Seltsam. Alles ist gleich, aber ich bin anders.",a:["R\u00fcckkehr"],opts:["R\u00fcckkehr","Sinnsuche","Lebensphase","Ungewissheit"],hint:"The feminine noun for returning home. R\u00fcck (back) + Kehr (turn). You turn back toward where you came from.",sSrc:"How was the return? Strange. Everything is the same, but I am different."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Aufbruch",src:"departure, setting out",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Masculine noun. Plural: die Aufbrueche.\n'Auf' (up) + 'Bruch' (break).",example:"A: Wann war dein Aufbruch?\nB: Vor zwei Jahren. Der Aufbruch war mutig.\nA: Aufbruch bedeutet, etwas Altes zu verlassen.\nB: Und etwas Neues zu wagen.",exampleSrc:"A: When was your departure?\nB: Two years ago. The departure was brave.\nA: Setting out means leaving something old behind.\nB: And daring something new.",funFact:"'Auf' (up) + 'Bruch' (break). Breaking up from where you are to go somewhere new. 'Der Aufbruch in ein neues Leben' (setting out into a new life). Breaking open, not breaking down."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Umzug",src:"a move, relocation",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Masculine noun. Plural: die Umzuege.\n'Um' (re-/around) + 'Zug' (pull/move).",example:"A: Wie war der Umzug nach Berlin?\nB: Stressig, aber aufregend.\nA: Ein Umzug verändert alles.\nB: Neue Stadt, neues Leben, neuer Mensch.",exampleSrc:"A: How was the move to Berlin?\nB: Stressful, but exciting.\nA: A move changes everything.\nB: New city, new life, new person.",funFact:"'Um' (re-/around) + 'Zug' (pull/move). You pull your life around to a new location. Germans move 4.5 times in their lifetime on average. 'Umzugskartons' (moving boxes) are a German life staple."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Sinnsuche",src:"search for meaning",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. No plural.\n'Sinn' (meaning) + 'Suche' (search).",example:"A: Bist du auf Sinnsuche?\nB: Ja, seit ich hier bin. Was bedeutet Heimat?\nA: Die Sinnsuche gehört zum Leben.\nB: Besonders wenn man zwischen zwei Welten lebt.",exampleSrc:"A: Are you searching for meaning?\nB: Yes, since I arrived here. What does home mean?\nA: The search for meaning is part of life.\nB: Especially when you live between two worlds.",funFact:"'Sinn' (meaning) + 'Suche' (search). The existential search for purpose. 'Auf Sinnsuche sein' (to be searching for meaning). Deeply embedded in German philosophy from Hegel to Heidegger."},
{type:"mc",q:"Er brach vor zwei Jahren in ein neues Leben auf. Was bedeutet 'aufbrechen'?",opts:["Etwas zerst\u00f6ren und kaputtmachen","In ein neues Abenteuer starten","Zu Hause bleiben und warten","Eine T\u00fcr verschliessen und sichern"],ans:"In ein neues Abenteuer starten",hint:"Auf (up/open) + brechen (to break). Not breaking down, but breaking open the door to something new. Setting out."}
]},
{id:"deu_r33l3b",title:"Nachdem ich weggegangen war (Teil 2)",icon:"\u23F3",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Nachdem ich weggegangen war (continued)",desc:"Continue practicing the vocabulary from this topic.",goals:["Review and practice key words"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Ungewissheit",src:"uncertainty",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. No plural.\n'Un-' + 'Gewissheit' (certainty).",example:"A: Wie gehst du mit Ungewissheit um?\nB: Schwer. Die Ungewissheit der Zukunft macht mir Angst.\nA: Ungewissheit gehört zum Leben.\nB: Ja, aber leichter wird es nicht.",exampleSrc:"A: How do you deal with uncertainty?\nB: With difficulty. The uncertainty of the future scares me.\nA: Uncertainty is part of life.\nB: Yes, but it does not get easier.",funFact:"'Un-' + 'Gewissheit' (certainty). Not knowing what comes next. The un- prefix negates certainty absolutely. 'Die Ungewissheit der Zukunft' is the human condition."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Vergaenglichkeit",src:"transience, impermanence",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. No plural.\n'Vergaenglich' (transient) + '-keit.'",example:"A: Glaubst du an die Vergaenglichkeit?\nB: Ja, alles vergeht. Nichts bleibt für immer.\nA: Die Vergaenglichkeit des Lebens ist schmerzhaft.\nB: Aber sie macht jeden Moment kostbar.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you believe in transience?\nB: Yes, everything passes. Nothing lasts forever.\nA: The transience of life is painful.\nB: But it makes every moment precious.",funFact:"'Vergaenglich' (transient) + '-keit.' Everything passes. German Romantic poetry is obsessed with Vergaenglichkeit. The beauty of a flower is in its fading."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Vorfreude",src:"anticipation, joy before the event",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. No plural.\n'Vor' (before) + 'Freude' (joy).",example:"A: Hast du Vorfreude auf Berlin?\nB: Ja, riesige Vorfreude!\nA: Vorfreude ist die schoenste Freude.\nB: Das sagt man in Deutschland. Und es stimmt.",exampleSrc:"A: Are you looking forward to Berlin?\nB: Yes, enormous anticipation!\nA: Anticipation is the best joy.\nB: That is what they say in Germany. And it is true.",funFact:"'Vor' (before) + 'Freude' (joy). 'Vorfreude ist die schoenste Freude' (Anticipation is the best joy). Only German has one word for the happiness of looking forward to something."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Wehmut",src:"wistfulness, bittersweet melancholy",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. No plural.\n'Weh' (pain) + 'Mut' (spirit/mood).",example:"A: Was ist Wehmut?\nB: Ein sanfter Schmerz. Schoen und traurig zugleich.\nA: Ich schaue alte Fotos mit Wehmut an.\nB: Das ist Wehmut: Die Schoenheit der Vergangenheit spueren.",exampleSrc:"A: What is wistfulness?\nB: A gentle pain. Beautiful and sad at once.\nA: I look at old photos with wistfulness.\nB: That is Wehmut: feeling the beauty of the past.",funFact:"'Weh' (pain) + 'Mut' (spirit/mood). Pain-spirit. A gentler form of sadness: not despair but a tender ache. Looking at old photos with Wehmut. Sweet sorrow."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Zufriedenheit",src:"contentment, satisfaction",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. No plural.\n'Zufrieden' (content) + '-heit.'",example:"A: Bist du zufrieden mit deinem Leben?\nB: Ja, ich habe innere Zufriedenheit gefunden.\nA: Zufriedenheit ist mehr als Glück.\nB: Es ist Frieden mit dem, was man hat.",exampleSrc:"A: Are you content with your life?\nB: Yes, I have found inner contentment.\nA: Contentment is more than happiness.\nB: It is peace with what you have.",funFact:"'Zufrieden' (content/satisfied) + '-heit.' 'Zu Frieden' = toward peace. Being content means being at peace with what you have. 'Innere Zufriedenheit' (inner contentment) is the goal."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"die Vergaenglichkeit",src:"transience, impermanence"},{trg:"die Vorfreude",src:"anticipation, joy before the event"},{trg:"die Wehmut",src:"wistfulness, bittersweet melancholy"},{trg:"die Zufriedenheit",src:"contentment, satisfaction"}]},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Zusammenhalt",src:"cohesion, solidarity",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Masculine noun. No plural.\n'Zusammen' (together) + 'Halt' (hold).",example:"A: Was hält eine Familie zusammen?\nB: Der Zusammenhalt. Das Fuereinander-da-Sein.\nA: Familienzusammenhalt ist stark.\nB: Er übersteht jede Entfernung.",exampleSrc:"A: What keeps a family together?\nB: Cohesion. Being there for each other.\nA: Family cohesion is strong.\nB: It survives any distance.",funFact:"'Zusammen' (together) + 'Halt' (hold). Holding together. What keeps a group unified when things get difficult. 'Familienzusammenhalt' (family cohesion) is the invisible glue."},
{type:"teach",trg:"wehmuetig",src:"wistful, bittersweet",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Adjective. 'Wehmut' + '-ig.'\n'Ein wehmeutiger Blick' (a wistful glance).",example:"A: Warum schaust du so wehmuetig?\nB: Ich denke an früher. Schoene Zeiten.\nA: Wehmuetig ist nicht traurig.\nB: Nein, es ist zaertlicher. Schoener Schmerz.",exampleSrc:"A: Why do you look so wistful?\nB: I am thinking of earlier times. Beautiful times.\nA: Wistful is not sad.\nB: No, it is gentler. Beautiful pain.",funFact:"'Wehmut' + '-ig.' Full of Wehmut. The adjective captures that tender ache of remembering beautiful things that are gone. Not despair, but sweet sorrow."},
{type:"teach",trg:"geborgen",src:"sheltered, safe, protected",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Past participle of 'bergen' (to shelter).\n'Sich geborgen fühlen.'",example:"A: Fuehlst du dich hier geborgen?\nB: Ja, dieses Haus gibt mir ein geborgenes Gefühl.\nA: Geborgen ist mehr als sicher.\nB: Es ist Waerme, Schutz, Liebe. Alles zusammen.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you feel sheltered here?\nB: Yes, this house gives me a sheltered feeling.\nA: Sheltered is more than safe.\nB: It is warmth, protection, love. All together.",funFact:"Past participle of 'bergen' (to shelter/rescue). The adjective behind Geborgenheit. What you feel in your mother's arms or your childhood home. More than safe: emotionally held."},
{type:"teach",trg:"liebgewonnen",src:"grown fond of",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Past participle of 'liebgewinnen.'\n'Eine liebgewonnene Gewohnheit.'",example:"A: Ist Berlin eine liebgewonnene Stadt?\nB: Ja, ich habe sie liebgewonnen.\nA: Liebgewonnen braucht Zeit.\nB: Genau. Keine Liebe auf den ersten Blick, sondern langsam gewachsen.",exampleSrc:"A: Is Berlin a city you have grown fond of?\nB: Yes, I have grown fond of it.\nA: Growing fond takes time.\nB: Exactly. Not love at first sight, but slowly grown.",funFact:"'Lieb' (dear) + 'gewonnen' (won/gained). You won something into your heart over time. Not love at first sight, but love through familiarity. 'Eine liebgewonnene Gewohnheit' is a habit close to your heart."},
{type:"teach",trg:"unersetzlich",src:"irreplaceable",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Adjective. 'Un-' + 'ersetzlich' (replaceable).\n'Ein unersetzlicher Mensch.'",example:"A: Ist deine Heimat unersetzlich?\nB: Ja, nichts kann sie ersetzen.\nA: Aber vielleicht kommt etwas Neues dazu.\nB: Ohne das Alte zu ersetzen. Beides ist unersetzlich.",exampleSrc:"A: Is your homeland irreplaceable?\nB: Yes, nothing can replace it.\nA: But perhaps something new is added.\nB: Without replacing the old. Both are irreplaceable.",funFact:"'Un-' + 'ersetzlich' (replaceable). What cannot be substituted. Nothing else fills the same space. The un- prefix creates the absolute."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"wehmuetig",src:"wistful, bittersweet"},{trg:"geborgen",src:"sheltered, safe, protected"},{trg:"liebgewonnen",src:"grown fond of"},{trg:"unersetzlich",src:"irreplaceable"}]},
{type:"teach",trg:"aufwachsen",src:"to grow up",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Separable, strong verb.\naufwachsen / wuchs auf / ist aufgewachsen.\n'In Berlin aufwachsen.'",example:"A: Wo bist du aufgewachsen?\nB: Ich bin am Mittelmeer aufgewachsen.\nA: War es schoen, dort aufzuwachsen?\nB: Ja, die Sonne, das Meer, die Familie.",exampleSrc:"A: Where did you grow up?\nB: I grew up by the Mediterranean.\nA: Was it nice to grow up there?\nB: Yes, the sun, the sea, the family.",funFact:"'Auf' (up) + 'wachsen' (to grow). Growing upward. Separable: 'Ich wuchs in einem Dorf auf.' Strong verb: aufwachsen / wuchs auf / ist aufgewachsen."},
{type:"teach",trg:"aufbrechen",src:"to set out, to depart",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Separable, strong verb.\naufbrechen / brach auf / ist aufgebrochen.",example:"A: Wann bist du aufgebrochen?\nB: Vor zwei Jahren. Ich brach in ein neues Leben auf.\nA: Aufbrechen braucht Mut.\nB: Und Vertrauen. Dass es sich lohnt.",exampleSrc:"A: When did you set out?\nB: Two years ago. I set out into a new life.\nA: Setting out takes courage.\nB: And trust. That it will be worth it.",funFact:"'Auf' (up/open) + 'brechen' (to break). Breaking open the door to something new. Separable. Strong verb: aufbrechen / brach auf / ist aufgebrochen. Not breaking down, but breaking free."},
{type:"teach",trg:"rückkehren",src:"to return",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Not separable. Uses sein in perfect.\nrückkehren / kehrte zurück / ist zurückgekehrt.",example:"A: Bist du in die Heimat zurückgekehrt?\nB: Ja, aber nur für eine Woche.\nA: Rückkehren ist nie einfach.\nB: Man erwartet, dass alles gleich ist. Aber man selbst hat sich verändert.",exampleSrc:"A: Did you return to your homeland?\nB: Yes, but only for a week.\nA: Returning is never easy.\nB: You expect everything to be the same. But you yourself have changed.",funFact:"'Rueck' (back) + 'kehren' (to turn). Not separable. Uses sein in perfect: 'Ich bin zurückgekehrt.' Turning back toward origin. The verb version of Rückkehr."},
{type:"teach",trg:"zurückdenken",src:"to think back, to reminisce",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Separable. zurückdenken / dachte zurück / zurückgedacht.\n'An die Kindheit zurückdenken.'",example:"A: Denkst du oft an früher zurück?\nB: Ja, ich denke an die Kindheit zurück.\nA: Zurückdenken macht wehmuetig.\nB: Aber es bewahrt die Erinnerungen.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you often think back?\nB: Yes, I think back to my childhood.\nA: Thinking back makes one wistful.\nB: But it preserves the memories.",funFact:"'Zurück' (back) + 'denken' (to think). Separable: 'Ich denke an die alten Zeiten zurück.' Sending your thoughts backward through time. The mental version of Rückkehr."},
{type:"fb",s:"Die {1} des Lebens macht jeden Moment kostbar.",a:["Vergaenglichkeit"],opts:["Zufriedenheit","Vorfreude","Vergaenglichkeit","Wehmut"],hint:"The feminine noun for transience, impermanence. Vergaenglich (transient) + -keit. Everything passes.",sSrc:"The transience of life makes every moment precious."},
{type:"teach",trg:"sobald",src:"as soon as",pos:"conj",gender:null,note:"Subordinating conjunction. Verb goes to the end.\nLinks two events: the second happens immediately after the first.",example:"A: Sobald ich ankomme, rufe ich an.\nB: Gut, ich warte dann.\nA: Sobald du zurück bist, reden wir.\nB: Versprochen. Sobald ich kann.",exampleSrc:"A: As soon as I arrive, I will call.\nB: Good, I will wait then.\nA: As soon as you are back, we will talk.\nB: Promised. As soon as I can.",funFact:"'Sobald' comes from 'so' + 'bald' (so soon). It implies the second action follows the first with no delay. In contrast, 'wenn' is general and 'als' is for single past events. 'Sobald' is the urgency connector."},
{type:"tip",title:"Temporalsaetze: Präzision in der Zeit",text:"At B2 level, temporal clauses become precise tools.\n- nachdem + Plusquamperfekt: 'Nachdem ich weggegangen war, verstand ich die Heimat besser.' (After I had left, I understood home better.) Past perfect in the subordinate clause, simple past/present in the main clause.\n- bevor: 'Bevor ich ging, nahm ich Abschied.' (Before I left, I said goodbye.) Same tense in both clauses.\n- sobald: 'Sobald ich ankomme, rufe ich an.' (As soon as I arrive, I will call.)\n- solange: 'Solange ich hier lebe, fühle ich mich geborgen.' (As long as I live here, I feel sheltered.)\n- während: 'Während ich schlief, schneite es.' (While I slept, it snowed.)\n- bis: 'Ich warte, bis du zurückkommst.' (I wait until you come back.)\n- seitdem: 'Seitdem ich Berlin kenne, hat sich alles verändert.' (Since I have known Berlin, everything has changed.)\n- kaum dass: 'Kaum dass er ankam, fühlte er sich zu Hause.' (Hardly had he arrived when he felt at home.) Literary.",deepDive:{title:"Tense sequence with nachdem",text:"The most important rule: nachdem requires a tense shift.\n\nNachdem + Plusquamperfekt, main clause + Präteritum:\n'Nachdem ich gegangen war, verstand ich.' (After I had left, I understood.)\n\nNachdem + Perfekt, main clause + Praesens:\n'Nachdem ich gegangen bin, verstehe ich.' (After I have left, I understand.)\n\nThe action in the nachdem clause is ALWAYS earlier than the one in the main clause. The Plusquamperfekt signals: this happened first. The other action followed."}},
{type:"verb_table",title:"Temporale Konnektoren: Übersicht",groups:[{label:"nachdem (nachdem): Zeitensprung erforderlich",rows:[{pronoun:"nachdem + Plusquamperfekt",form:"Nachdem ich gegangen war, verstand ich.",src:"After I had left, I understood."},{pronoun:"nachdem + Perfekt",form:"Nachdem ich gegangen bin, verstehe ich.",src:"After I have left, I understand."}]},{label:"Weitere temporale Konnektoren (Verb am Ende)",rows:[{pronoun:"bevor (before)",form:"Bevor ich ging, nahm ich Abschied.",src:"Before I left, I said goodbye."},{pronoun:"sobald (as soon as)",form:"Sobald ich ankomme, rufe ich an.",src:"As soon as I arrive, I'll call."},{pronoun:"solange (as long as)",form:"Solange ich hier bin, bin ich glücklich.",src:"As long as I'm here, I'm happy."},{pronoun:"während (while)",form:"Während ich schlief, schneite es.",src:"While I slept, it snowed."},{pronoun:"bis (until)",form:"Ich warte, bis du kommst.",src:"I wait until you come."},{pronoun:"seitdem (since)",form:"Seitdem ich hier lebe, hat sich alles verändert.",src:"Since I've lived here, everything changed."},{pronoun:"kaum dass (hardly had)",form:"Kaum dass er ankam, fühlte er sich wohl.",src:"Hardly had he arrived, he felt at home."}]}],note:"All temporal connectors send the verb to the end of the subordinate clause. With nachdem, the tense shift is obligatory."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Nachdem ich zwei Jahre in Berlin gelebt hatte, fühlt sich das Weggehen seltsam an.' Warum steht Plusquamperfekt im nachdem-Satz?",opts:["Weil es Pr\u00e4sens ist und die Gegenwart anzeigt","Weil es ein Wunsch ist und kein Ereignis","Weil es sich um indirekte Rede handelt","Weil das Leben vor dem Weggehen stattfand"],ans:"Weil das Leben vor dem Weggehen stattfand",hint:"This temporal conjunction requires the earlier action in Plusquamperfekt. Living (earlier), then feeling strange (later)."},
{type:"fb",s:"{1} ich nach Deutschland ging, war dieses Zimmer die ganze Welt.",a:["Bevor"],opts:["Bevor","Nachdem","Während","Seitdem"],hint:"The room was the whole world at that time. Then came the departure. Which temporal conjunction places the subordinate clause BEFORE the main clause event?",sSrc:"Before I went to Germany, this room was the whole world."},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'der Zusammenhalt'?",opts:["contentment, satisfaction","wistfulness, bittersweet melancholy","search for meaning","cohesion, solidarity"],ans:"cohesion, solidarity",hint:"zusammen (together) + Halt (hold/support). Holding together as a community."},
{type:"fb",s:"Warum schaust du so {1}?",a:["wehmuetig"],opts:["wehmuetig","der Aufbruch","geborgen","die Vorfreude"],hint:"Weh (pain) + Mut (spirit/mood). A bittersweet mood, sad but not bitter.",sSrc:"Why do you look so wistful?"},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'liebgewonnen'?",opts:["grown fond of","a move, relocation","wistfulness, bittersweet melancholy","search for meaning"],ans:"grown fond of",hint:"lieb (dear) + gewonnen (won/gained). Something you have come to love over time."},
{type:"fb",s:"Ist deine Heimat {1}?",a:["unersetzlich"],opts:["aufbrechen","unersetzlich","der Aufbruch","zurückdenken"],hint:"un- + ersetzen (to replace) + -lich. Nothing else can take its place.",sSrc:"Is your homeland irreplaceable?"},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'zurückdenken'?",opts:["to think back, to reminisce","search for meaning","transience, impermanence","a move, relocation"],ans:"to think back, to reminisce",hint:"Consider what this word expresses in everyday conversation."},
{type:"fb",s:"Die {1} über die Zukunft quaelt ihn jede Nacht.",a:["Ungewissheit"],opts:["Ungewissheit","Nostalgie","Sehnsucht","Geborgenheit"],hint:"Not knowing what will happen. The state of being uncertain. Un + Gewissheit (certainty).",sSrc:"The uncertainty about the future torments him every night."}
]},
{id:"deu_r33l4",title:"Stolz auf, abhängig von",icon:"\uD83D\uDD17",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Stolz auf, abhängig von",desc:"German adjectives pair with fixed prepositions. The preposition determines the case. There is no shortcut: you must learn each combination. But patterns help, and the Heimat journey provides the perfect context.",goals:["Master adjective-preposition combinations","Express precise emotional states","Describe relationships between people, places, and feelings"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"stolz auf",src:"proud of",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Stolz auf + Akkusativ.\n'Ich bin stolz auf meine Fortschritte.'",example:"A: Bist du stolz auf dein neues Leben?\nB: Ja, ich bin sehr stolz auf alles, was ich erreicht habe.\nA: Worauf bist du am stolzesten?\nB: Auf meinen Mut. Stolz auf den Neuanfang.",exampleSrc:"A: Are you proud of your new life?\nB: Yes, I am very proud of everything I have achieved.\nA: What are you most proud of?\nB: My courage. Proud of the new beginning.",funFact:"The preposition auf demands accusative. You direct your pride ONTO something. The most common Adj+Praep combination in German. 'Stolz auf' is the first one every learner should know."},
{type:"teach",trg:"abhängig von",src:"dependent on",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Abhängig von + Dativ.\n'Abhängig von den Umständen.'",example:"A: Bist du abhängig von anderen?\nB: Nein, ich bin unabhängig geworden.\nA: Früher war ich abhängig von Hilfe.\nB: Jetzt nicht mehr. Aber abhängig vom Wetter bin ich noch.",exampleSrc:"A: Are you dependent on others?\nB: No, I have become independent.\nA: Earlier I was dependent on help.\nB: Not anymore. But I am still dependent on the weather.",funFact:"Von always takes dative. Hanging from something: your fate hangs from external factors. 'Unabhängig' (independent) is the opposite. The prefix un- frees you from the dependency."},
{type:"teach",trg:"interessiert an",src:"interested in",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Interessiert an + Dativ.\n'Interessiert an neuen Erfahrungen.'",example:"A: Bist du interessiert an der deutschen Kultur?\nB: Ja, sehr interessiert an allem, was Deutschland ausmacht.\nA: Woran bist du besonders interessiert?\nB: An der Geschichte und der Sprache.",exampleSrc:"A: Are you interested in German culture?\nB: Yes, very interested in everything that makes Germany.\nA: What are you particularly interested in?\nB: In the history and the language.",funFact:"An + Dativ when it means 'at/in.' Your interest is directed at something. 'Woran bist du interessiert?' uses the da-/wo- compound for an + Dativ."},
{type:"teach",trg:"überzeugt von",src:"convinced of",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Überzeugt von + Dativ.\n'Überzeugt von dieser Idee.'",example:"A: Bist du überzeugt von deiner Entscheidung?\nB: Ja, ich bin fest überzeugt davon.\nA: Wovon bist du überzeugt?\nB: Dass Berlin meine Heimat ist.",exampleSrc:"A: Are you convinced of your decision?\nB: Yes, I am firmly convinced of it.\nA: What are you convinced of?\nB: That Berlin is my home.",funFact:"Von + Dativ. Your conviction comes from something. The evidence convinced you. 'Davon überzeugt' uses the da-compound to reference what you believe in."},
{type:"fb",s:"Ich bin {1} von meiner Entscheidung, nach Berlin zu gehen.",a:["\u00fcberzeugt"],opts:["\u00fcberzeugt","abh\u00e4ngig","entt\u00e4uscht","begeistert"],hint:"The adjective paired with 'von + Dativ' meaning firmly believing in something. Your conviction comes from evidence.",sSrc:"I am convinced of my decision to go to Berlin."},
{type:"teach",trg:"zufrieden mit",src:"satisfied with",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Zufrieden mit + Dativ.\n'Zufrieden mit meinem Leben.'",example:"A: Bist du zufrieden mit deinem Leben in Berlin?\nB: Ja, sehr zufrieden damit.\nA: Womit bist du am zufriedensten?\nB: Mit den Menschen und der Freiheit.",exampleSrc:"A: Are you satisfied with your life in Berlin?\nB: Yes, very satisfied with it.\nA: What are you most satisfied with?\nB: With the people and the freedom.",funFact:"Mit always takes dative. Contentment goes together with its source. 'Zu Frieden' = toward peace. When you are zufrieden mit something, you are at peace with it."},
{type:"teach",trg:"verantwortlich fuer",src:"responsible for",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Verantwortlich für + Akkusativ.\n'Verantwortlich für das Ergebnis.'",example:"A: Wer ist verantwortlich für das Projekt?\nB: Ich bin verantwortlich für alles.\nA: Verantwortlich für sein eigenes Glück.\nB: Genau. Jeder ist verantwortlich für sein Leben.",exampleSrc:"A: Who is responsible for the project?\nB: I am responsible for everything.\nA: Responsible for your own happiness.\nB: Exactly. Everyone is responsible for their life.",funFact:"Für takes accusative. You answer for something. 'Verantwortlich' comes from 'Antwort' (answer). Being responsible means being the one who answers for the result."},
{type:"teach",trg:"begeistert von",src:"enthusiastic about",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Begeistert von + Dativ.\n'Begeistert von Berlin.'",example:"A: Bist du begeistert von Berlin?\nB: Ja, ich bin total begeistert von der Stadt.\nA: Wovon bist du am meisten begeistert?\nB: Von der Energie und der Vielfalt.",exampleSrc:"A: Are you enthusiastic about Berlin?\nB: Yes, I am totally enthusiastic about the city.\nA: What are you most enthusiastic about?\nB: About the energy and the diversity.",funFact:"Your enthusiasm comes from Berlin. Von + Dativ. 'Begeistert' literally means 'filled with spirit' (Geist). When Berlin fills you with its Geist, you are begeistert."},
{type:"mc",q:"Ich bin begeistert von Berlin! Welche Pr\u00e4position verlangt 'begeistert'?",opts:["begeistert auf + Akkusativ","begeistert von + Dativ","begeistert mit + Dativ","begeistert f\u00fcr + Akkusativ"],ans:"begeistert von + Dativ",hint:"Your enthusiasm comes FROM the source. This preposition always governs origin or source, triggering one specific case."},
{type:"teach",trg:"enttäuscht von",src:"disappointed in/by",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Enttäuscht von + Dativ.\n'Enttäuscht von der Rückkehr.'",example:"A: Bist du enttäuscht von der Rückkehr?\nB: Ein bisschen. Ich hatte mehr erwartet.\nA: Wovon genau bist du enttäuscht?\nB: Davon, dass nichts mehr so ist wie früher.",exampleSrc:"A: Are you disappointed by the return?\nB: A little. I had expected more.\nA: What exactly are you disappointed by?\nB: By the fact that nothing is like before.",funFact:"The disappointment originates from the experience. Von + Dativ. 'Ent-täuscht' means 'de-deceived.' You were under an illusion, and reality removed it."},
{type:"teach",trg:"neugierig auf",src:"curious about",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Neugierig auf + Akkusativ.\n'Neugierig auf die Zukunft.'",example:"A: Bist du neugierig auf die Zukunft?\nB: Ja, sehr neugierig auf alles, was kommt.\nA: Worauf bist du am neugierigsten?\nB: Auf das nächsste Kapitel meines Lebens.",exampleSrc:"A: Are you curious about the future?\nB: Yes, very curious about everything that comes.\nA: What are you most curious about?\nB: About the next chapter of my life.",funFact:"Your curiosity is directed onto something ahead. Auf + Akkusativ. 'Neugierig' literally means 'new-greedy.' Greedy for the new. A beautiful word for curiosity."},
{type:"teach",trg:"verbunden mit",src:"connected with",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Verbunden mit + Dativ.\n'Verbunden mit der Heimat.'",example:"A: Fuehlst du dich verbunden mit Berlin?\nB: Ja, tief verbunden mit dieser Stadt.\nA: Womit fuehlst du dich am stärksten verbunden?\nB: Mit den Erinnerungen und den Menschen.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you feel connected with Berlin?\nB: Yes, deeply connected with this city.\nA: What do you feel most strongly connected with?\nB: With the memories and the people.",funFact:"Your bond goes together with the place. Mit + Dativ. Deeper than just 'connected to.' 'Tiefe Verbundenheit' (deep connection) is the noun form. The invisible threads between you and a place."},
{type:"teach",trg:"dankbar fuer",src:"grateful for",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Dankbar für + Akkusativ.\n'Dankbar für die Erfahrung.'",example:"A: Bist du dankbar für deine Zeit in Berlin?\nB: Unendlich dankbar dafuer.\nA: Wofür bist du am dankbarsten?\nB: Für die Menschen, die mich aufgenommen haben.",exampleSrc:"A: Are you grateful for your time in Berlin?\nB: Infinitely grateful for it.\nA: What are you most grateful for?\nB: For the people who took me in.",funFact:"Your gratitude is directed toward something. Für + Akkusativ. 'Dankbar' comes from 'Dank' (thanks). Same pattern as the noun: 'der Dank fuer' (gratitude for)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"gewöhnt an",src:"accustomed to",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Gewöhnt an + Akkusativ.\n'Gewöhnt an das Berliner Wetter.'",example:"A: Hast du dich an das Wetter gewöhnt?\nB: Ja, ich bin gewöhnt an die Kaelte.\nA: Woran muss man sich in Berlin gewöhnen?\nB: An den Winter. Und an die Direktheit der Berliner.",exampleSrc:"A: Have you gotten used to the weather?\nB: Yes, I am accustomed to the cold.\nA: What do you have to get used to in Berlin?\nB: The winter. And the directness of Berliners.",funFact:"An + Akkusativ when it means 'to' (direction). You have adapted yourself to something. 'Sich an etwas gewöhnen' (to get used to something) is the verb form."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"neugierig auf",src:"curious about"},{trg:"verbunden mit",src:"connected with"},{trg:"dankbar fuer",src:"grateful for"},{trg:"gewöhnt an",src:"accustomed to"}]},
{type:"teach",trg:"neidisch auf",src:"envious of",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Neidisch auf + Akkusativ.\n'Neidisch auf den Erfolg anderer.'",example:"A: Bist du neidisch auf andere?\nB: Manchmal. Neidisch auf ihr ruhiges Leben.\nA: Neid ist ein schlechter Ratgeber.\nB: Stimmt. Besser dankbar als neidisch.",exampleSrc:"A: Are you envious of others?\nB: Sometimes. Envious of their calm life.\nA: Envy is a bad advisor.\nB: True. Better grateful than envious.",funFact:"Your envy is directed onto someone else's achievement. Auf + Akkusativ. 'Neid' (envy) is one of the seven deadly sins. German distinguishes 'Neid' (resentful envy) from 'Eifersucht' (jealousy in love)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"vertraut mit",src:"familiar with",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Vertraut mit + Dativ.\n'Vertraut mit der deutschen Kultur.'",example:"A: Bist du vertraut mit der deutschen Bürokratie?\nB: Leider ja. Sehr vertraut damit.\nA: Womit bist du inzwischen vertraut?\nB: Mit Formularen, Fristen und Sachbearbeitern.",exampleSrc:"A: Are you familiar with German bureaucracy?\nB: Unfortunately yes. Very familiar with it.\nA: What are you familiar with by now?\nB: With forms, deadlines, and case workers.",funFact:"Your familiarity goes together with the subject. Mit + Dativ. From 'vertrauen' (to trust). What you know well enough to trust. Not just knowing about, but knowing deeply."},
{type:"fb",s:"Ich bin {1} an der deutschen Kultur, besonders an der Geschichte.",a:["interessiert"],opts:["gew\u00f6hnt","angewiesen","interessiert","vertraut"],hint:"The adjective paired with 'an + Dativ' meaning curious and engaged with a subject. From 'Interesse.'",sSrc:"I am interested in German culture, especially in the history."},
{type:"mc",q:"Alte Menschen sind oft {blank} Hilfe von anderen.",opts:["angewiesen auf","vertraut mit","gewöhnt an","neidisch auf"],ans:"angewiesen auf",hint:"Dependent on, reliant on. You need help from someone else and cannot manage without it."}
]},
{id:"deu_r33l4b",title:"Stolz auf, abhängig von (Teil 2)",icon:"\uD83D\uDD17",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Stolz auf, abhängig von (continued)",desc:"Continue practicing the vocabulary from this topic.",goals:["Review and practice key words"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"angewiesen auf",src:"dependent on, reliant on",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Angewiesen auf + Akkusativ.\n'Angewiesen auf Hilfe.' Stärker als 'abhängig von.'",example:"A: Bist du auf Hilfe angewiesen?\nB: Nicht mehr. Früher war ich darauf angewiesen.\nA: Worauf bist du noch angewiesen?\nB: Auf mein Wörterbuch. Das brauche ich noch.",exampleSrc:"A: Are you reliant on help?\nB: Not anymore. I used to be reliant on it.\nA: What are you still reliant on?\nB: My dictionary. I still need that.",funFact:"Stronger than 'abhängig von.' You are directed toward what you need. Auf + Akkusativ. 'Angewiesen' means 'pointed toward.' Your need points at the source of help."},
{type:"teach",trg:"damals",src:"back then, at that time",pos:"adv",gender:null,note:"Adverb. 'Da' (there/then) + 'mals' (time).\nMore precise than 'früher.'",example:"A: Erinnerst du dich an damals?\nB: Ja, damals war alles anders.\nA: Damals hatte ich noch Angst.\nB: Und heute? Heute bin ich stolz auf mich.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you remember back then?\nB: Yes, back then everything was different.\nA: Back then I was still afraid.\nB: And today? Today I am proud of myself.",funFact:"'Da' (there/then) + 'mals' (time). Points to a specific time in the past. More precise than 'früher' (earlier/in the past). 'Damals in Berlin' sets a clear temporal frame."},
{type:"teach",trg:"einst",src:"once, formerly",pos:"adv",gender:null,note:"Adverb. From Old High German 'einest.'\nLiterary and elevated. More poetic than 'damals.'",example:"A: Einst war dieses Haus meine ganze Welt.\nB: Und heute?\nA: Heute ist die Welt groesser geworden.\nB: Aber die Erinnerung an einst bleibt.",exampleSrc:"A: Once this house was my whole world.\nB: And today?\nA: Today the world has become bigger.\nB: But the memory of what once was remains.",funFact:"Used in fairy tales ('Es war einst...'), einst is more poetic than damals. It traces back to Old High German 'einest' (once). The word itself sounds like a memory fading into silence."},
{type:"teach",trg:"heutzutage",src:"nowadays",pos:"adv",gender:null,note:"Adverb. 'Heute' (today) + 'zu' (to) + 'Tage' (days).\nThe contrast partner to 'damals' and 'einst.'",example:"A: Heutzutage lebe ich in Berlin.\nB: Und damals?\nA: Damals lebte ich am Mittelmeer.\nB: Heutzutage ist alles anders. Besser.",exampleSrc:"A: Nowadays I live in Berlin.\nB: And back then?\nA: Back then I lived by the Mediterranean.\nB: Nowadays everything is different. Better.",funFact:"'Heute' (today) + 'zu' (to) + 'Tage' (days). Three words fused into one adverb. The contrast partner to damals and einst. Damals vs. heutzutage frames every life story."},
{type:"tip",title:"Adjektive + Praepositionen: Das System",text:"German adjectives take fixed prepositions, and the preposition determines the case. No rule predicts which adjective takes which preposition, but patterns help.\n\nEmotions directed ONTO something use auf (Akkusativ): stolz auf (proud of), neugierig auf (curious about), angewiesen auf (reliant on), neidisch auf (envious of).\n\nEmotions that come FROM something use von (Dativ): abh\u00e4ngig von (dependent on), \u00fcberzeugt von (convinced of), begeistert von (enthusiastic about), entt\u00e4uscht von (disappointed by).\n\nEmotions that go TOGETHER WITH something use mit (Dativ): zufrieden mit (satisfied with), verbunden mit (connected with), vertraut mit (familiar with).\n\nOther common pairings: verantwortlich f\u00fcr and dankbar f\u00fcr (Akkusativ), interessiert an (Dativ), gew\u00f6hnt an (Akkusativ).",deepDive:{title:"Why fixed prepositions?",text:"In German, adjective-preposition pairs are idiomatic. You say 'stolz auf' and not 'stolz über' or 'stolz von.' There is no logical explanation. Historically these combinations solidified over centuries.\n\nTip: Learn each pair as a unit. Not 'stolz' and then 'auf,' but 'stolz-auf' as one word. Like a phone number: inseparable.\n\nThe da-/wo- compound forms replace the preposition:\nstolz auf etwas = stolz darauf\nzufrieden mit etwas = zufrieden damit\ninteressiert an etwas = interessiert daran"}},
{type:"verb_table",title:"Adjektive + Praepositionen: Kasustabelle",groups:[{label:"auf + Akkusativ (gerichtet auf)",rows:[{pronoun:"stolz auf",form:"Ich bin stolz auf meinen Erfolg.",src:"I am proud of my success."},{pronoun:"neugierig auf",form:"Neugierig auf die Zukunft.",src:"Curious about the future."},{pronoun:"neidisch auf",form:"Neidisch auf seinen Erfolg.",src:"Envious of his success."},{pronoun:"angewiesen auf",form:"Angewiesen auf Hilfe.",src:"Reliant on help."}]},{label:"von + Dativ (kommend von)",rows:[{pronoun:"abhängig von",form:"Abhängig von den Umständen.",src:"Dependent on circumstances."},{pronoun:"überzeugt von",form:"Überzeugt von der Idee.",src:"Convinced of the idea."},{pronoun:"begeistert von",form:"Begeistert von der Stadt.",src:"Enthusiastic about the city."}]},{label:"mit + Dativ (zusammen mit)",rows:[{pronoun:"zufrieden mit",form:"Zufrieden mit dem Ergebnis.",src:"Satisfied with the result."},{pronoun:"verbunden mit",form:"Verbunden mit der Heimat.",src:"Connected with home."},{pronoun:"vertraut mit",form:"Vertraut mit der Kultur.",src:"Familiar with the culture."}]}],note:"The preposition determines the case. Auf + Akkusativ, von + Dativ, mit + Dativ, für + Akkusativ."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Verumius ist stolz auf sein neues Leben.' Welchen Kasus verlangt 'auf' hier?",opts:["Dativ","Genitiv","Nominativ","Akkusativ"],ans:"Akkusativ",hint:"'Stolz auf' always requires the same case. 'Sein neues Leben' shows the ending."},
{type:"fb",s:"Ich bin zufrieden {1} meinem Leben in Berlin.",a:["mit"],opts:["mit","auf","von","fuer"],hint:"'Zufrieden' takes the preposition meaning 'together with.' Satisfaction goes together.",sSrc:"I am satisfied with my life in Berlin."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Nachdem er aufgewachsen war, brach er in ein neues Leben auf.' Warum steht Plusquamperfekt im nachdem-Satz?",opts:["Beide Handlungen laufen gleichzeitig und parallel ab","Weil das Aufwachsen vor dem Aufbrechen stattfand","Das Aufbrechen war das erste, frühere Ereignis","Es handelt sich um einen unerfüllten Wunsch"],ans:"Weil das Aufwachsen vor dem Aufbrechen stattfand",hint:"This temporal conjunction marks the earlier event. Plusquamperfekt shows it was complete before the main clause action began."},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"{1} er nach Berlin gezogen war, wurde er {2} auf seine neue Heimat.",blanks:{"1":"Nachdem","2":"stolz"},pool:["Nachdem","stolz","Bevor","zufrieden","Während","dankbar"],hint:"A temporal conjunction indicating sequence (the move came first) plus an adjective-preposition pair. The adjective describes how he felt about his new home.",sSrc:"After he had moved to Berlin, he became proud of his new home."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"stolz auf",src:"proud of (+Akk)"},{trg:"abhängig von",src:"dependent on (+Dat)"},{trg:"zufrieden mit",src:"satisfied with (+Dat)"},{trg:"dankbar fuer",src:"grateful for (+Akk)"}]},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'damals'?",opts:["envious of","back then, at that time","nowadays","enthusiastic about"],ans:"back then, at that time",hint:"An adverb pointing firmly to the past. Often paired with memories and stories."},
{type:"fb",s:"{1} war dieses Haus meine ganze Welt.",a:["einst"],opts:["überzeugt von","gewöhnt an","einst","damals"],hint:"A literary/poetic word for 'once upon a time'. More elevated than 'früher'.",sSrc:"Once this house was my whole world."},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'heutzutage'?",opts:["nowadays","envious of","enthusiastic about","curious about"],ans:"nowadays",hint:"heute (today) + zu + Tage (days). Literally: in today's days. The modern era."},
{type:"fb",s:"Viele ländliche Regionen sind auf staatliche Förderung {1}.",a:["angewiesen"],opts:["angewiesen","verbunden","gewöhnt","begeistert"],hint:"Dependent on, reliant on. This adjective-preposition combination uses auf + Akkusativ.",sSrc:"Many rural regions are dependent on government funding."}
]},
{id:"deu_r33l5",title:"Die Angst vor, die Sehnsucht nach",icon:"\u2693",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Die Angst vor, die Sehnsucht nach",desc:"Verumius sits on a bench by the Mediterranean. The sun is setting. He realizes where his Heimat truly lies.",goals:["Learn noun + fixed prepositions (die Angst vor, die Sehnsucht nach)","Combine all three grammar constructs","Describe abstract relationships between feelings and concepts"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Angst vor",src:"fear of",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Angst vor + Dativ. You stand before what frightens you.\n'Die Angst vor der Zukunft' (the fear of the future).",example:"A: Hast du Angst vor der Pr\u00fcfung?\nB: Ja, die Angst vor dem Versagen ist gro\u00df.\nA: Die Angst vor Ver\u00e4nderung ist normal.\nB: Aber man darf sich nicht l\u00e4hmen lassen.",exampleSrc:"A: Are you afraid of the exam?\nB: Yes, the fear of failure is great.\nA: The fear of change is normal.\nB: But you must not let yourself be paralyzed.",funFact:"Angst vor + Dativ. Vor means 'before/in front of.' You stand before what frightens you. English borrowed 'angst' directly from German. Freud made Angst a worldwide word."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Einfluss auf",src:"influence on",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Einfluss auf + Akkusativ. Your influence flows onto something.\n'Der Einfluss auf die Entscheidung' (the influence on the decision).",example:"A: Welchen Einfluss auf die Politik hast du?\nB: Ich gehe w\u00e4hlen. Das ist mein Einfluss.\nA: Der Einfluss auf die Umwelt ist messbar.\nB: Jeder kann etwas ver\u00e4ndern.",exampleSrc:"A: What influence on politics do you have?\nB: I go vote. That is my influence.\nA: The influence on the environment is measurable.\nB: Everyone can change something.",funFact:"Ein (in) + Fluss (flow). Influence literally means 'inflow.' Your Einfluss flows into a decision. Auf + Akkusativ because the influence is directed onto something."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Hoffnung auf",src:"hope for",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Hoffnung auf + Akkusativ. You direct your hope onto something.\n'Die Hoffnung auf eine bessere Zukunft.'",example:"A: Die Hoffnung auf Frieden stirbt zuletzt.\nB: Das stimmt. Man darf nie aufgeben.\nA: Hast du Hoffnung auf Besserung?\nB: Immer. Die Hoffnung auf Gutes treibt mich an.",exampleSrc:"A: The hope for peace dies last.\nB: That is true. One must never give up.\nA: Do you have hope for improvement?\nB: Always. The hope for good things drives me.",funFact:"Hoffnung auf + Akkusativ. 'Die Hoffnung stirbt zuletzt' (Hope dies last) is a German proverb. You direct your hope onto something ahead of you. Auf points forward."},
{type:"mc",q:"Hast du Angst vor der Zukunft? Welchen Kasus verlangt 'vor' bei 'Angst vor'?",opts:["Akkusativ","Genitiv","Dativ","Nominativ"],ans:"Dativ",hint:"You stand 'before' what frightens you. The preposition 'vor' in this fixed combination always takes the same case."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Bedarf an",src:"need for",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Bedarf an + Dativ. What you require, what you need at hand.\n'Der Bedarf an Fachkr\u00e4ften' (the need for skilled workers).",example:"A: Es gibt einen gro\u00dfen Bedarf an Lehrern.\nB: Ja, der Bedarf an Fachkr\u00e4ften w\u00e4chst.\nA: Wie gro\u00df ist der Bedarf an Wohnungen?\nB: Riesig. Besonders in Berlin.",exampleSrc:"A: There is a great need for teachers.\nB: Yes, the need for skilled workers is growing.\nA: How great is the need for apartments?\nB: Enormous. Especially in Berlin.",funFact:"Bedarf an + Dativ. An here means 'at/of.' Your need exists at the thing required. 'Bedarf anmelden' (to register a need). A formal word common in business and policy."},
{type:"fb",s:"Mein {1} auf mein eigenes Leben war nie gr\u00f6\u00dfer.",a:["Einfluss"],opts:["Einfluss","Bedarf","Stolz","Wunsch"],hint:"The masculine noun for influence. Ein (in) + Fluss (flow). Your influence flows onto something. Paired with auf + Akkusativ.",sSrc:"My influence on my own life has never been greater."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Freude \u00fcber",src:"joy about",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Freude \u00fcber + Akkusativ. Your joy flows over the cause.\n'Die Freude \u00fcber die R\u00fcckkehr' (the joy about the return).",example:"A: Die Freude \u00fcber das Geschenk war riesig.\nB: Ja, er hat sich so gefreut.\nA: Die Freude \u00fcber den Erfolg teilen wir.\nB: Zusammen feiern ist das Sch\u00f6nste.",exampleSrc:"A: The joy about the gift was enormous.\nB: Yes, he was so happy.\nA: We share the joy about the success.\nB: Celebrating together is the best.",funFact:"Freude \u00fcber + Akkusativ. \u00dcber (about/over). 'Freude sch\u00f6ner G\u00f6tterfunken' is the opening of Schiller's Ode to Joy, set by Beethoven. The EU anthem. Freude is powerful."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Stolz auf",src:"pride in",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Stolz auf + Akkusativ. Same preposition as the adjective stolz auf.\n'Der Stolz auf die eigene Leistung.'",example:"A: Der Stolz auf seine Kinder ist sichtbar.\nB: Ja, er ist ein stolzer Vater.\nA: Empfindest du Stolz auf dein Deutsch?\nB: Auf jeden Fall. Zwei Jahre harte Arbeit.",exampleSrc:"A: The pride in his children is visible.\nB: Yes, he is a proud father.\nA: Do you feel pride in your German?\nB: Absolutely. Two years of hard work.",funFact:"Stolz auf + Akkusativ. The noun version matches the adjective: stolz auf. Same preposition, same case. 'Nationalstolz' (national pride) is complicated in Germany since 1945."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Erinnerung an",src:"memory of",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Erinnerung an + Akkusativ. Your memory reaches toward the past.\n'Die Erinnerung an die Kindheit.'",example:"A: Die Erinnerung an den Sommer bleibt.\nB: Ja, an manche Tage erinnere ich mich immer.\nA: Welche Erinnerung an Berlin ist die sch\u00f6nste?\nB: Der erste Fr\u00fchling im Tiergarten.",exampleSrc:"A: The memory of the summer remains.\nB: Yes, I always remember some days.\nA: Which memory of Berlin is the most beautiful?\nB: The first spring in the Tiergarten.",funFact:"Erinnerung an + Akkusativ. An (at/directed at). Your memory reaches at the past. 'Erinnerungsst\u00fcck' (memento). Related to 'erinnern' (to remember), which brings something back into your inner self."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Wunsch nach",src:"wish for",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Wunsch nach + Dativ. You wish after something.\n'Der Wunsch nach Geborgenheit' (the wish for security).",example:"A: Der Wunsch nach Freiheit ist universell.\nB: Und der Wunsch nach Geborgenheit auch.\nA: Was ist dein gr\u00f6\u00dfter Wunsch nach Ver\u00e4nderung?\nB: Mehr Zeit f\u00fcr die Menschen, die mir wichtig sind.",exampleSrc:"A: The wish for freedom is universal.\nB: And the wish for security too.\nA: What is your biggest wish for change?\nB: More time for the people who matter to me.",funFact:"Wunsch nach + Dativ. Nach (after/toward). You wish after something you do not yet have. 'Wunschdenken' (wishful thinking). 'Sich etwas w\u00fcnschen' (to wish for something)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Sehnsucht nach",src:"longing for",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Sehnsucht nach + Dativ. The deepest German emotion with its\nfixed preposition. You yearn after what is distant.",example:"A: Die Sehnsucht nach der Heimat ist stark.\nB: Ja, man vermisst, was man liebt.\nA: Empfindest du Sehnsucht nach dem Meer?\nB: Immer. Die Sehnsucht nach dem Meer h\u00f6rt nie auf.",exampleSrc:"A: The longing for home is strong.\nB: Yes, you miss what you love.\nA: Do you feel longing for the sea?\nB: Always. The longing for the sea never stops.",funFact:"Sehnsucht nach + Dativ. The most German of emotions with its fixed preposition. Romantic poets built entire philosophies around Sehnsucht nach dem Unerreichbaren (longing for the unreachable)."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"der Stolz auf",src:"pride in"},{trg:"die Erinnerung an",src:"memory of"},{trg:"der Wunsch nach",src:"wish for"},{trg:"die Sehnsucht nach",src:"longing for"}]},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Vertrauen in",src:"trust in",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"Vertrauen in + Akkusativ. You place your trust into something.\n'Das Vertrauen in die Zukunft.'",example:"A: Das Vertrauen in die Regierung sinkt.\nB: Leider. Vertrauen muss man verdienen.\nA: Hast du Vertrauen in die Zukunft?\nB: Ja. Man muss optimistisch bleiben.",exampleSrc:"A: Trust in the government is declining.\nB: Unfortunately. Trust must be earned.\nA: Do you have trust in the future?\nB: Yes. One must stay optimistic.",funFact:"Vertrauen in + Akkusativ. In (into). You place your trust into something. 'Vertrauensverlust' (loss of trust). Trust flows into its object. Building Vertrauen takes time; losing it takes a moment."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Dank f\u00fcr",src:"gratitude for",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Dank f\u00fcr + Akkusativ. Same pattern as dankbar f\u00fcr.\n'Der Dank f\u00fcr die Unterst\u00fctzung.'",example:"A: Mein Dank f\u00fcr deine Hilfe ist gro\u00df.\nB: Gern geschehen. Das war selbstverst\u00e4ndlich.\nA: Der Dank f\u00fcr die Gastfreundschaft geb\u00fchrt euch.\nB: Wir freuen uns, dass du da warst.",exampleSrc:"A: My gratitude for your help is great.\nB: You are welcome. That was a matter of course.\nA: The gratitude for the hospitality belongs to you.\nB: We are glad you were here.",funFact:"Dank f\u00fcr + Akkusativ. 'Dank' as noun means 'thanks/gratitude.' 'Dankeschreiben' (thank-you letter). Same preposition as dankbar f\u00fcr. 'Zum Dank f\u00fcr' (as thanks for)."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Welche Pr\u00e4position verlangt das Nomen 'Erinnerung'?",opts:["Erinnerung von","Erinnerung nach","Erinnerung an","Erinnerung auf"],ans:"Erinnerung an",hint:"Your memory reaches AT/toward the past. The noun pairs with a fixed preposition that also serves as a direction marker."}
]},
{id:"deu_r33l5b",title:"Die Angst vor, die Sehnsucht nach (Teil 2)",icon:"\u2693",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Die Angst vor, die Sehnsucht nach (continued)",desc:"Continue practicing the vocabulary from this topic.",goals:["Review and practice key words"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Interesse an",src:"interest in",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"Interesse an + Dativ. Your interest is located at the subject.\n'Das Interesse an fremden Kulturen.'",example:"A: Das Interesse an Sprachen w\u00e4chst.\nB: Besonders das Interesse an Deutsch.\nA: Woher kommt dein Interesse an Geschichte?\nB: Von meinem Gro\u00dfvater. Er hat viel erz\u00e4hlt.",exampleSrc:"A: The interest in languages is growing.\nB: Especially the interest in German.\nA: Where does your interest in history come from?\nB: From my grandfather. He told many stories.",funFact:"Interesse an + Dativ. An (at). Your interest exists at the subject. 'Interessenkonflikt' (conflict of interest). The noun matches the adjective: interessiert an + Dativ."},
{type:"teach",trg:"irgendwann",src:"someday, at some point",pos:"adv",gender:null,note:"Irgend (some) + wann (when). Not a specific time, but eventually.\n'Irgendwann komme ich zur\u00fcck.'",example:"A: Wann besuchst du deine Familie?\nB: Irgendwann. Vielleicht im Sommer.\nA: Irgendwann m\u00fcssen wir alle gehen.\nB: Aber nicht heute. Heute bleiben wir.",exampleSrc:"A: When will you visit your family?\nB: Someday. Maybe in summer.\nA: Someday we all have to leave.\nB: But not today. Today we stay.",funFact:"The irgend- prefix adds vagueness to question words. Irgendwann (some-when), irgendwo (somewhere), irgendwer (someone). The series creates beautiful imprecision."},
{type:"teach",trg:"k\u00fcnftig",src:"future, forthcoming",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"From Kunft (coming, as in Zukunft). What is coming toward us.\n'K\u00fcnftige Generationen' (future generations).",example:"A: K\u00fcnftige Generationen werden es anders sehen.\nB: Ja, die Welt ver\u00e4ndert sich.\nA: Was sind deine k\u00fcnftigen Pl\u00e4ne?\nB: Ich bleibe in Berlin. Das steht fest.",exampleSrc:"A: Future generations will see it differently.\nB: Yes, the world is changing.\nA: What are your future plans?\nB: I am staying in Berlin. That is certain.",funFact:"The adjectival form of Zukunft (future), built on Kunft (coming). Also works as an adverb: 'Kuenftig esse ich weniger Fleisch' (From now on I will eat less meat). The future is always arriving."},
{type:"teach",trg:"l\u00e4ngst",src:"long since, long ago",pos:"adv",gender:null,note:"Superlative of lang used as adverb. Something completed far in\nthe past. 'Das habe ich l\u00e4ngst gewusst.'",example:"A: Wusstest du, dass Berlin seine Heimat ist?\nB: Ja, das habe ich l\u00e4ngst gewusst.\nA: Die Entscheidung war l\u00e4ngst gefallen.\nB: Er brauchte nur Zeit, es zu begreifen.",exampleSrc:"A: Did you know that Berlin is his home?\nB: Yes, I have known that for a long time.\nA: The decision had long since been made.\nB: He just needed time to understand it.",funFact:"Superlative of 'lang' used as adverb. 'L\u00e4ngst vergessen' (long since forgotten). 'L\u00e4ngst \u00fcberf\u00e4llig' (long overdue). It implies the action was completed well before now."},
{type:"teach",trg:"seitdem",src:"since then",pos:"adv",gender:null,note:"Seit (since) + dem (then). Marks the starting point of ongoing change.\nBoth conjunction and adverb.",example:"A: Er kam 2024 nach Berlin. Seitdem lebt er dort.\nB: Seitdem hat sich alles ver\u00e4ndert.\nA: Seitdem er Deutsch spricht, f\u00fchlt er sich zu Hause.\nB: Sprache ver\u00e4ndert alles.",exampleSrc:"A: He came to Berlin in 2024. Since then he has lived there.\nB: Since then everything has changed.\nA: Since he speaks German, he feels at home.\nB: Language changes everything.",funFact:"Seit (since) + dem (then). As conjunction: 'Seitdem ich hier lebe...' As adverb: 'Seitdem hat sich alles ver\u00e4ndert.' Marks when change began and that it continues."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"irgendwann",src:"someday, at some point"},{trg:"k\u00fcnftig",src:"future, forthcoming"},{trg:"l\u00e4ngst",src:"long since, long ago"},{trg:"seitdem",src:"since then"}]},
{type:"teach",trg:"von jeher",src:"from time immemorial, always",pos:"adv",gender:null,note:"Von (from) + je (ever) + her (from there). Since the beginning of\ntime. Elevated and literary.",example:"A: Von jeher suchen Menschen eine Heimat.\nB: Das ist ein menschliches Grundbed\u00fcrfnis.\nA: War er von jeher ein Wanderer?\nB: Ja, von jeher zog es ihn in die Ferne.",exampleSrc:"A: From time immemorial people have been searching for a home.\nB: That is a basic human need.\nA: Was he always a wanderer?\nB: Yes, he was always drawn to distant places.",funFact:"Von (from) + je (ever) + her (from there). 'Von jeher' reaches all the way back to the beginning. More literary than 'schon immer.' Fairy-tale language that elevates everyday observations."},
{type:"teach",trg:"zeitlebens",src:"for one's entire life, lifelong",pos:"adv",gender:null,note:"Zeit + Lebens (of life). A single adverb covering an entire lifespan.\n'Zeitlebens suchte er eine Heimat.'",example:"A: Zeitlebens suchte er einen Ort zum Bleiben.\nB: Und er fand ihn in Berlin.\nA: Manche Menschen reisen zeitlebens.\nB: Andere werden sesshaft. Beides ist gut.",exampleSrc:"A: All his life he searched for a place to stay.\nB: And he found it in Berlin.\nA: Some people travel their whole lives.\nB: Others settle down. Both are fine.",funFact:"Zeit (time) + Lebens (genitive of Leben). One word for an entire lifetime. 'Zeitlebens' collapses a whole biography into a single adverb. Powerful in its compression."},
{type:"tip",title:"Nomen + Pr\u00e4positionen: Das Substantiv-System",text:"Just as adjectives take fixed prepositions, so do nouns. Often the adjective and noun pairs match: 'stolz auf' pairs with 'der Stolz auf' (both Akkusativ), and 'interessiert an' pairs with 'das Interesse an' (both Dativ).\n\nKey groupings by preposition:\n- auf (Akk) for influence, hope, and pride: Einfluss auf, Hoffnung auf, Stolz auf\n- vor (Dat) for fear: Angst vor\n- nach (Dat) for longing and wishes: Sehnsucht nach, Wunsch nach\n- an takes Dativ for need and interest (Bedarf an, Interesse an) but Akkusativ for memory (Erinnerung an)\n- in (Akk) for trust: Vertrauen in\n- f\u00fcr (Akk) for gratitude: Dank f\u00fcr\n- \u00fcber (Akk) for joy: Freude \u00fcber\n\nNo rule predicts which noun takes which preposition. Memorize each pair as a unit.",deepDive:{title:"Noun-preposition pairs: The system",text:"Just as adjectives have fixed prepositions, so do nouns. Often the pairs match: stolz auf / der Stolz auf. But not always. You must memorize each pair.\n\nKey patterns:\n- auf + Akk: influence flows onto, hope directed onto, pride directed onto\n- vor + Dat: you stand before what you fear\n- nach + Dat: you yearn after what is distant\n- an + Dat/Akk: depends on direction (Bedarf an = need at, Erinnerung an = memory directed at)\n- in + Akk: trust placed into\n- f\u00fcr + Akk: gratitude directed for\n- \u00fcber + Akk: joy flows over"}},
{type:"mc",q:"'Die Sehnsucht nach der Heimat.' Warum steht nach + Dativ?",opts:["nach verlangt in diesem Kontext immer den Akkusativ","nach ist Sehnsuchts-Pr\u00e4position und verlangt Dativ","die Pr\u00e4position ist v\u00f6llig zuf\u00e4llig und bedeutungslos","die korrekte Pr\u00e4position w\u00e4re hier stattdessen auf"],ans:"nach ist Sehnsuchts-Pr\u00e4position und verlangt Dativ",hint:"This noun of deep longing pairs with a fixed word partner. That partner also governs direction of motion and always requires one specific case."},
{type:"fb",s:"Die Erinnerung {1} die Kindheit bleibt f\u00fcr immer.",a:["an"],opts:["an","auf","nach","von"],hint:"'Erinnerung' pairs with a preposition meaning 'toward something.' Direction to the memory target.",sSrc:"The memory of childhood remains forever."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Seitdem er zur\u00fcck ist, ist er dankbar f\u00fcr die Erfahrung.' Welche Konstrukte werden kombiniert?",opts:["nur temporal, nichts anderes","nur Adj+Pr\u00e4p ohne weiteres","keine besonderen Konstrukte hier","Temporalsatz + Adj+Pr\u00e4p"],ans:"Temporalsatz + Adj+Pr\u00e4p",hint:"'Seitdem' introduces the time clause. 'Dankbar fuer' pairs a describing word with a fixed connector."},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"{1} er gegangen war, wuchs seine Sehnsucht {2} der Heimat.",blanks:{"1":"Nachdem","2":"nach"},pool:["Nachdem","nach","Bevor","auf","W\u00e4hrend","von"],hint:"Two structures: a temporal conjunction that always takes Plusquamperfekt, followed by a noun-preposition combination expressing longing.",sSrc:"After he had left, his longing for home grew."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"die Angst vor",src:"fear of (+Dat)"},{trg:"die Sehnsucht nach",src:"longing for (+Dat)"},{trg:"der Einfluss auf",src:"influence on (+Akk)"},{trg:"die Erinnerung an",src:"memory of (+Akk)"}]},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'das Interesse an'?",opts:["interest in","future, forthcoming","someday, at some point","fear of"],ans:"interest in",hint:"A neuter noun + preposition 'an'. Curiosity or engagement directed at something."},
{type:"fb",s:"{1}. Vielleicht im Sommer.",a:["irgendwann"],opts:["die Freude \\u00fcber","irgendwann","die Erinnerung an","der Stolz auf"],hint:"irgend (some/any) + wann (when). At some unspecified point in time.",sSrc:"Someday. Maybe in summer."},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'von jeher'?",opts:["pride in","wish for","trust in","from time immemorial, always"],ans:"from time immemorial, always",hint:"von (from) + je (ever) + her (from/since). Since the very beginning, as far back as memory goes."},
{type:"fb",s:"Er verlor nie die {1} auf ein besseres Leben.",a:["Hoffnung"],opts:["Hoffnung","Angst","Sehnsucht","Erinnerung"],hint:"The feeling that something good will happen in the future. Paired with 'auf' + Akkusativ.",sSrc:"He never lost the hope for a better life."}
]},
{id:"deu_r33l6",title:"Heimat ist kein Ort",icon:"\ud83c\udfe0",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Heimat ist kein Ort",desc:"Verumius returns to Berlin. The door opens. The plants are alive. Hildi looked after them.",goals:["Combine all three grammar constructs in complex sentences","Practice temporal, adjective, and noun-preposition constructs together","Learn the final Heimat vocabulary"]},
{type:"fb",s:"Verumius hat sich in Berlin {1}. Er hat dort Wurzeln geschlagen.",a:["verwurzelt"],opts:["verwurzelt","entwurzelt","eingelebt","beheimatet"],hint:"The past participle of the verb meaning to take root. Ver- + Wurzel + -t. His roots have grown deep in Berlin.",sSrc:"Verumius has taken root in Berlin. He put down roots there."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Seele",src:"soul",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From Old High German 'seula.' German Romanticism made the\nSeele central to philosophy and poetry.",example:"A: Was ist die Seele eines Ortes?\nB: Das Gef\u00fchl, das er in dir ausl\u00f6st.\nA: Hat Berlin eine Seele?\nB: Ja, eine wilde, freie Seele.",exampleSrc:"A: What is the soul of a place?\nB: The feeling it triggers in you.\nA: Does Berlin have a soul?\nB: Yes, a wild, free soul.",funFact:"Hegel, Schelling, and Novalis all wrote about the Seele. 'Die Seele baumeln lassen' (to let the soul dangle) means to relax deeply. The word goes back to Old High German 'seula.' A uniquely German image."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Ruhepol",src:"point of calm, anchor",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Ruhe (calm) + Pol (pole). The still point in a spinning life.\n'Berlin ist mein Ruhepol.'",example:"A: Was ist dein Ruhepol?\nB: Meine Wohnung in Berlin. Dort finde ich Ruhe.\nA: Jeder Mensch braucht einen Ruhepol.\nB: Stimmt. Einen Ort der Stille.",exampleSrc:"A: What is your anchor?\nB: My apartment in Berlin. There I find calm.\nA: Every person needs an anchor.\nB: True. A place of stillness.",funFact:"Ruhe (calm) + Pol (pole). Like the North Pole on a compass: a fixed point that everything else spins around. 'Er ist der Ruhepol der Familie' (He is the family's anchor)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Obdach",src:"shelter, roof over one's head",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"Ob (over/above) + Dach (roof). The most basic level of Heimat.\n'Obdachlose' lack this roof.",example:"A: Jeder Mensch braucht ein Obdach.\nB: Ja, ein Dach \u00fcber dem Kopf ist grundlegend.\nA: Was bedeutet obdachlos?\nB: Ohne Dach. Ohne Schutz vor Regen und K\u00e4lte.",exampleSrc:"A: Every person needs shelter.\nB: Yes, a roof over one's head is fundamental.\nA: What does homeless mean?\nB: Without a roof. Without protection from rain and cold.",funFact:"Ob (over) + Dach (roof). 'Obdachlos' (homeless) means literally 'without an over-roof.' The most basic form of Heimat: having a Dach. Without Obdach, Geborgenheit is impossible."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Er ist der Ruhepol der Familie.' Was ist ein Ruhepol?",opts:["Ein lauter, dominanter Anf\u00fchrer der Gruppe","Der feste Punkt der Ruhe, um den sich alles dreht","Ein weit entfernter Verwandter der Familie","Ein Ort f\u00fcr sportliche Aktivit\u00e4ten"],ans:"Der feste Punkt der Ruhe, um den sich alles dreht",hint:"Calm + Pol (pole). Like a compass center: the fixed, still point around which everything else moves."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Zuflucht",src:"refuge",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Zu (to) + Flucht (flight). Where you flee to. Not running away\nbut running toward safety.",example:"A: Berlin war seine Zuflucht.\nB: Ja, dort fand er Sicherheit.\nA: Wo findest du Zuflucht?\nB: In der Musik. Sie ist meine Zuflucht.",exampleSrc:"A: Berlin was his refuge.\nB: Yes, there he found safety.\nA: Where do you find refuge?\nB: In music. It is my refuge.",funFact:"Zu (to) + Flucht (flight). 'Zuflucht suchen' (to seek refuge). 'Zufluchtsort' (place of refuge). You are not fleeing from something but fleeing to safety. The zu makes all the difference."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Mutterland",src:"motherland",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"Mutter (mother) + Land. More personal than Vaterland.\nThe land that mothered you.",example:"A: Was ist das Mutterland der Philosophie?\nB: Griechenland, sagt man.\nA: Und dein Mutterland?\nB: Das Land, in dem ich aufgewachsen bin.",exampleSrc:"A: What is the motherland of philosophy?\nB: Greece, they say.\nA: And your motherland?\nB: The country where I grew up.",funFact:"Mutter (mother) + Land. The nurturing homeland. More emotional than Vaterland. Also used metaphorically: 'Das Mutterland des Jazz' (the motherland of jazz). The land that gave birth to something."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Vaterland",src:"fatherland",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"Vater (father) + Land. Historically loaded in German.\nModern Germans prefer 'Heimat' or simply 'Deutschland.'",example:"A: Ist Vaterland ein schwieriges Wort?\nB: Ja, nach 1945 wurde es problematisch.\nA: Was sagen die meisten Deutschen?\nB: Heimat. Oder einfach Deutschland.",exampleSrc:"A: Is Vaterland a difficult word?\nB: Yes, after 1945 it became problematic.\nA: What do most Germans say?\nB: Heimat. Or simply Germany.",funFact:"Vater (father) + Land. 'F\u00fcrs Vaterland' (for the fatherland) was the slogan of two World Wars. After 1945, the word carries heavy historical baggage. Modern Germans use it carefully, if at all."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Gem\u00fct",src:"temperament, disposition",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"From Mut (mood/spirit). When your inner nature is at peace,\nthe world feels gem\u00fctlich.",example:"A: Er hat ein fr\u00f6hliches Gem\u00fct.\nB: Ja, er ist immer gut gelaunt.\nA: Woher kommt das Wort gem\u00fctlich?\nB: Von Gem\u00fct. Wenn das Gem\u00fct friedlich ist.",exampleSrc:"A: He has a cheerful disposition.\nB: Yes, he is always in a good mood.\nA: Where does the word gem\u00fctlich come from?\nB: From Gem\u00fct. When the temperament is peaceful.",funFact:"Did you know 'gemuetlich' (cozy) comes from Gemuet? When your inner nature (Mut = mood/spirit) is peaceful, everything feels warm. Gemuetlichkeit is Germany's coziest cultural export."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Sicherheitsgef\u00fchl",src:"sense of security",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"Sicherheit (security) + s + Gef\u00fchl (feeling). With Fugen-s.\nWhat Geborgenheit provides.",example:"A: Das Sicherheitsgef\u00fchl in Berlin ist hoch.\nB: Ja, man f\u00fchlt sich sicher.\nA: Was gibt dir ein Sicherheitsgef\u00fchl?\nB: Gute Nachbarn und eine sichere Wohnung.",exampleSrc:"A: The sense of security in Berlin is high.\nB: Yes, one feels safe.\nA: What gives you a sense of security?\nB: Good neighbors and a safe apartment.",funFact:"Sicherheit (security) + s + Gef\u00fchl (feeling). The Fugen-s links the compounds. At three words deep, this is classic German: Sicherheit-s-gef\u00fchl. What Geborgenheit provides in concrete form."},
{type:"fb",s:"Das {1} in Berlin ist hoch. Man f\u00fchlt sich sicher.",a:["Sicherheitsgef\u00fchl"],opts:["Lebensgef\u00fchl","Zugeh\u00f6rigkeitsgef\u00fchl","Sicherheitsgef\u00fchl","Fernweh"],hint:"A compound noun: the word for 'security' + linking-s + the word for 'emotion.' What Geborgenheit provides concretely.",sSrc:"The sense of security in Berlin is high. One feels safe."}
]},
{id:"deu_r33l6b",title:"Heimat ist kein Ort (Teil 2)",icon:"\ud83c\udfe0",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Heimat ist kein Ort (continued)",desc:"Continue practicing the vocabulary from this topic.",goals:["Review and practice key words"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"verwurzelt",src:"rooted",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Ver- + Wurzel (root) + -t. Past participle as adjective.\nYour roots have grown deep.",example:"A: Bist du verwurzelt in Berlin?\nB: Ja, tief verwurzelt. Seit zwei Jahren.\nA: Verwurzelt sein braucht Zeit.\nB: Stimmt. Wurzeln wachsen langsam.",exampleSrc:"A: Are you rooted in Berlin?\nB: Yes, deeply rooted. For two years.\nA: Being rooted takes time.\nB: True. Roots grow slowly.",funFact:"Ver- + Wurzel (root) + -t. 'Tief verwurzelt in der Gemeinschaft' (deeply rooted in the community). The adjective captures a state of belonging that took time to develop. Trees need years. So do people."},
{type:"teach",trg:"zufrieden",src:"content, satisfied",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Zu (to) + Frieden (peace). At peace with what you have.\nNot needing more. 'Zufrieden mit dem Leben.'",example:"A: Bist du zufrieden mit deinem Leben?\nB: Ja, ich bin sehr zufrieden.\nA: Was macht dich zufrieden?\nB: Gute Freunde und eine sch\u00f6ne Wohnung.",exampleSrc:"A: Are you satisfied with your life?\nB: Yes, I am very satisfied.\nA: What makes you content?\nB: Good friends and a nice apartment.",funFact:"Zu (to) + Frieden (peace). 'Zufriedenheit' (contentment). Being content means being at peace with what you have. Not needing more. The most German form of happiness: quiet satisfaction."},
{type:"teach",trg:"ortsbezogen",src:"place-related, local",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Ort (place) + s + bezogen (related). Memories tied to specific\nlocations. With Fugen-s.",example:"A: Sind deine Erinnerungen ortsbezogen?\nB: Ja, jeder Ort weckt andere Gef\u00fchle.\nA: Ortsbezogene Daten zeigen, wo du warst.\nB: Manchmal ist das n\u00fctzlich, manchmal nicht.",exampleSrc:"A: Are your memories place-related?\nB: Yes, every place triggers different feelings.\nA: Location-based data shows where you have been.\nB: Sometimes that is useful, sometimes not.",funFact:"Ort (place) + s + bezogen (related). With Fugen-s. 'Ortsbezogene Erinnerungen' (place-related memories). Memories tied to specific locations. Also used in tech: 'ortsbezogene Dienste' (location-based services)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"ruheliebend",src:"peace-loving, quiet-natured",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Ruhe (calm) + liebend (loving). A compound present participle.\nSomeone who loves calm.",example:"A: Bist du ein ruheliebender Mensch?\nB: Ja, ich brauche Stille zum Denken.\nA: Ruheliebende Nachbarn sind Gold wert.\nB: Stimmt. Laut ist einfach anstrengend.",exampleSrc:"A: Are you a peace-loving person?\nB: Yes, I need silence to think.\nA: Quiet-natured neighbors are worth gold.\nB: True. Loud is just exhausting.",funFact:"Ruhe (calm) + liebend (loving). A compound present participle used as adjective. 'Ein ruheliebender Mensch' loves Ruhe. The opposite of 'gesellig' (sociable). Not antisocial, just peace-seeking."},
{type:"teach",trg:"verwurzeln",src:"to take root, to become rooted",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Ver- + Wurzel + -n. Reflexive: sich verwurzeln.\nThe process of growing roots in a new place.",example:"A: Es dauert, sich an einem neuen Ort zu verwurzeln.\nB: Ja, aber mit der Zeit schafft man es.\nA: Wie hat er sich in Berlin verwurzelt?\nB: Durch Freunde, Arbeit und Sprache.",exampleSrc:"A: It takes time to take root in a new place.\nB: Yes, but with time you manage.\nA: How did he take root in Berlin?\nB: Through friends, work, and language.",funFact:"Ver- + Wurzel (root) + -n. Not separable. 'Sich in einer Gemeinschaft verwurzeln' (to take root in a community). The process version of verwurzelt. Growing roots is active work."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"zufrieden",src:"content, satisfied"},{trg:"ortsbezogen",src:"place-related, local"},{trg:"ruheliebend",src:"peace-loving, quiet-natured"},{trg:"verwurzeln",src:"to take root, to become rooted"}]},
{type:"teach",trg:"beheimaten",src:"to be home to, to house",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Be- + Heimat + -en. Non-separable. The city performs the act\nof being a Heim.",example:"A: Berlin beheimatet viele Kulturen.\nB: Ja, \u00fcber 190 Nationalit\u00e4ten.\nA: Welche Stadt beheimatet die meisten Museen?\nB: Berlin. \u00dcber 170 Museen.",exampleSrc:"A: Berlin is home to many cultures.\nB: Yes, over 190 nationalities.\nA: Which city is home to the most museums?\nB: Berlin. Over 170 museums.",funFact:"Be- + Heimat + -en. Non-separable. 'Berlin beheimatet 3,7 Millionen Menschen.' The be- prefix makes Heimat into a verb. A city does the act of being a home."},
{type:"teach",trg:"einleben",src:"to settle in, to acclimatize",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Ein (in) + leben (to live). Reflexive: sich einleben.\nSeparable: 'Ich habe mich eingelebt.'",example:"A: Hast du dich in Berlin eingelebt?\nB: Ja, nach ein paar Monaten.\nA: Wie schnell lebt man sich ein?\nB: Das ist bei jedem anders.",exampleSrc:"A: Have you settled in to Berlin?\nB: Yes, after a few months.\nA: How quickly does one settle in?\nB: That is different for everyone.",funFact:"Ein (in) + leben (to live). Separable. 'Sich einleben' means living yourself into a new place. The ein- prefix suggests entering. You enter a new life by living into it."},
{type:"teach",trg:"sch\u00e4tzen",src:"to appreciate, to estimate",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Two meanings: valuing and guessing. 'Ich sch\u00e4tze das sehr'\n(I appreciate that). 'Ich sch\u00e4tze, es dauert eine Stunde.'",example:"A: Ich sch\u00e4tze deine Ehrlichkeit.\nB: Danke, das bedeutet mir viel.\nA: Wie alt sch\u00e4tzt du ihn?\nB: Ich sch\u00e4tze, er ist Anfang drei\u00dfig.",exampleSrc:"A: I appreciate your honesty.\nB: Thanks, that means a lot to me.\nA: How old do you estimate he is?\nB: I estimate he is in his early thirties.",funFact:"The root word is 'Schatz' (treasure). To treasure something means to appreciate it. The second meaning (to estimate) comes from appraising treasure's value. Two meanings, one beautiful origin."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Nachdem er sich eingelebt hatte, war er stolz auf sein neues Leben und empfand keine Angst vor der Zukunft mehr.' Welche drei Konstrukte?",opts:["nur Temporalsatz, kein Adj+Pr\u00e4p vorhanden","nur Adj+Pr\u00e4p und Nomen+Pr\u00e4p kombiniert","nur Nomen+Pr\u00e4p ohne Temporalsatz","Temporalsatz + Adj+Pr\u00e4p + Nomen+Pr\u00e4p"],ans:"Temporalsatz + Adj+Pr\u00e4p + Nomen+Pr\u00e4p",hint:"Count each structural type: a temporal clause with a sequence rule, an emotion expressed with a describing word plus fixed connector, and a noun that pairs with a specific connector."},
{type:"fb",s:"Die Sehnsucht {1} Berlin war st\u00e4rker als alles andere.",a:["nach"],opts:["nach","auf","vor","von"],hint:"'Sehnsucht' pairs with a directional preposition. The longing reaches toward the distant place.",sSrc:"The longing for Berlin was stronger than everything else."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Kaum dass er die T\u00fcr \u00f6ffnete, sah er die Pflanzen.' Was bedeutet 'kaum dass'?",opts:["bevor (zeitlich vorher)","kaum hatte er / sobald","w\u00e4hrend (gleichzeitig)","bis (Endpunkt einer Zeitspanne)"],ans:"kaum hatte er / sobald",hint:"This structure marks something that happened almost immediately after another event. Literary and dramatic timing."},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"{1} er zur\u00fcckgekehrt war, f\u00fchlte er sich {2} mit seinem Leben.",blanks:{"1":"Nachdem","2":"zufrieden"},pool:["Nachdem","zufrieden","Bevor","stolz","Seitdem","verbunden"],hint:"A temporal conjunction indicating sequence plus an adjective-preposition pair. He felt contentment with his life after returning.",sSrc:"After he had returned, he felt satisfied with his life."},
{type:"fb",s:"Er hat sich in Berlin {1}.",a:["eingelebt"],opts:["verwurzelt","beheimatet","eingelebt","gesch\u00e4tzt"],hint:"He has settled into his new surroundings over time. A reflexive, separable verb. The prefix describes direction inward, the base verb describes daily existence.",sSrc:"He has settled in to Berlin."},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"Berlin {1} viele Kulturen. Verumius hat sich dort {2}.",blanks:{"1":"beheimatet","2":"verwurzelt"},pool:["beheimatet","verwurzelt","einleben","sch\u00e4tzen","pflegen","entwurzelt"],hint:"Which verb means 'is home to'? And which participle describes that roots have grown?",sSrc:"Berlin is home to many cultures. Verumius has taken root there."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"Geborgenheit",src:"feeling of being sheltered"},{trg:"Ruhepol",src:"point of calm/anchor"},{trg:"Zuflucht",src:"refuge"},{trg:"verwurzelt",src:"rooted"}]},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'ortsbezogen'?",opts:["motherland","to be home to, to house","refuge","place-related, local"],ans:"place-related, local",hint:"Two parts: a noun for location + a participle meaning connected to. Tied to or defined by a specific spot."},
{type:"fb",s:"Es dauert, sich an einem neuen Ort zu {1}.",a:["verwurzeln"],opts:["ruheliebend","das Sicherheitsgef\\u00fchl","verwurzeln","die Seele"],hint:"ver- + Wurzel (root). To grow roots in a new place, to become deeply established.",sSrc:"It takes time to take root in a new place."},
{type:"mc",q:"In der Nationalhymne wird Deutschland als {blank} bezeichnet.",opts:["Vaterland","Mutterland","Heimatland","Geburtsland"],ans:"Vaterland",hint:"The patriotic word for one's country. Vater (father) + Land (land). Used in the national anthem."},
{type:"fb",s:"Sie hat ein sonniges {1}. Nichts bringt sie aus der Ruhe.",a:["Gemüt"],opts:["Gemüt","Gewissen","Gefühl","Gedanke"],hint:"Your inner temperament or disposition. A uniquely German concept for emotional nature.",sSrc:"She has a sunny temperament. Nothing upsets her."}
]},
{id:"deu_r33l7",title:"Jedes Wort eine Erinnerung",icon:"\ud83d\udcdd",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Jedes Wort eine Erinnerung",desc:"Show what you can do. All three grammar constructs, the full Heimat vocabulary, and new modal particles are waiting for you.",goals:["Prove mastery of all three grammar constructs","Learn key German modal particles","Master complex sentences with temporal and prepositional precision"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Ortskenntnis",src:"local knowledge, knowledge of a place",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Ort (place) + s + Kenntnis (knowledge). With Fugen-s.\nKnowing where the bakery is, which shortcut to take.",example:"A: Taxifahrer brauchen Ortskenntnis.\nB: Ja, sie m\u00fcssen jede Stra\u00dfe kennen.\nA: Hast du Ortskenntnis in Berlin?\nB: Nach zwei Jahren kenne ich mich gut aus.",exampleSrc:"A: Taxi drivers need local knowledge.\nB: Yes, they have to know every street.\nA: Do you have local knowledge of Berlin?\nB: After two years I know my way around well.",funFact:"Ort (place) + s + Kenntnis (knowledge). With Fugen-s. Before GPS, London taxi drivers had to pass 'The Knowledge.' German Ortskenntnis is the equivalent: knowing your city by heart."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Zugeh\u00f6rigkeitsgef\u00fchl",src:"sense of belonging",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"Zugeh\u00f6rigkeit (belonging) + s + Gef\u00fchl (feeling). With Fugen-s.\nAt 24 letters, a classic German compound.",example:"A: Was gibt dir ein Zugeh\u00f6rigkeitsgef\u00fchl?\nB: Wenn Nachbarn mich gr\u00fc\u00dfen.\nA: Verumius hat endlich ein Zugeh\u00f6rigkeitsgef\u00fchl.\nB: Ja, er geh\u00f6rt nach Berlin.",exampleSrc:"A: What gives you a sense of belonging?\nB: When neighbors greet me.\nA: Verumius finally has a sense of belonging.\nB: Yes, he belongs in Berlin.",funFact:"Zugeh\u00f6rigkeit (belonging) + s + Gef\u00fchl (feeling). At 24 letters, a classic German compound. The feeling of belonging somewhere. What Verumius finally found after two years of searching."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Versprechen",src:"a promise",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"Ver- + Sprechen (speaking). When you speak forth, you bind\nyourself. Also: 'sich versprechen' = to misspeak.",example:"A: Ein Versprechen muss man halten.\nB: Ja, gebrochene Versprechen verletzen.\nA: Gibst du mir ein Versprechen?\nB: Ich verspreche, zur\u00fcckzukommen.",exampleSrc:"A: A promise must be kept.\nB: Yes, broken promises hurt.\nA: Will you give me a promise?\nB: I promise to come back.",funFact:"Ver- + Sprechen (speaking). 'Ein Versprechen halten' (to keep a promise). 'Ein Versprechen brechen' (to break a promise). Also: 'sich versprechen' means to misspeak. Two meanings, one verb."},
{type:"mc",q:"Ein Versprechen muss man halten. Was passiert, wenn man es bricht?",opts:["Es st\u00e4rkt die Beziehung und das Vertrauen","Nichts Schlimmes, es ist nur ein Wort","Es verletzt Vertrauen und Verbundenheit","Es zeigt Zuverl\u00e4ssigkeit und Ehrlichkeit"],ans:"Es verletzt Vertrauen und Verbundenheit",hint:"'Ein Versprechen brechen' (to break a promise). The broken word damages the invisible bonds between people."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Verwandtschaft",src:"relatives, kinship",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Verwandt (related) + -schaft. The collective noun for everyone\nyou are related to. Often invoked at Weihnachten.",example:"A: Die ganze Verwandtschaft kommt zu Weihnachten.\nB: Oh nein, alle Tanten und Onkel?\nA: Ja, die komplette Verwandtschaft.\nB: Dann brauchen wir einen gr\u00f6\u00dferen Tisch.",exampleSrc:"A: The entire family is coming for Christmas.\nB: Oh no, all aunts and uncles?\nA: Yes, the complete relatives.\nB: Then we need a bigger table.",funFact:"Verwandt (related) + -schaft (collective suffix). 'Weitl\u00e4ufige Verwandtschaft' (distant relatives). The -schaft suffix groups individuals into a collective. Your Verwandtschaft is everyone who shares your blood."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Zuverl\u00e4ssigkeit",src:"reliability",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Zuverl\u00e4ssig (reliable) + -keit. What Germans value above\nalmost everything else.",example:"A: Zuverl\u00e4ssigkeit ist mir sehr wichtig.\nB: Mir auch. Man muss sich aufeinander verlassen k\u00f6nnen.\nA: Deutsche Zuverl\u00e4ssigkeit ist ber\u00fchmt.\nB: Manchmal Klischee, manchmal Wahrheit.",exampleSrc:"A: Reliability is very important to me.\nB: To me too. One must be able to rely on each other.\nA: German reliability is famous.\nB: Sometimes clich\u00e9, sometimes truth.",funFact:"Zuverl\u00e4ssig (reliable) + -keit. 'Deutsche Zuverl\u00e4ssigkeit' is both a stereotype and a real cultural value. 'Sich auf jemanden verlassen' (to rely on someone). Zuverl\u00e4ssigkeit makes trust possible."},
{type:"teach",trg:"ja",src:"(particle: surprise/emphasis)",pos:"part",gender:null,note:"As modal particle (not 'yes'): adds emphasis or surprise.\n'Das ist ja toll!' (That is wow great!)",example:"A: Das ist ja wunderbar!\nB: Ja, ich bin auch \u00fcberrascht.\nA: Du bist ja schon da!\nB: Ich bin fr\u00fcher gekommen.",exampleSrc:"A: That is (wow) wonderful!\nB: Yes, I am surprised too.\nA: You are already here (oh)!\nB: I came earlier.",funFact:"Ja as particle does not mean 'yes.' It signals the speaker's reaction to something unexpected or notable. 'Du bist ja schon da!' (You're already here!). One of the first particles learners master."},
{type:"fb",s:"Verumius hat endlich ein {1} in Berlin gefunden.",a:["Zugeh\u00f6rigkeitsgef\u00fchl"],opts:["Zugeh\u00f6rigkeitsgef\u00fchl","Sicherheitsgef\u00fchl","Versprechen","Andenken"],hint:"A 24-letter compound noun for the emotion of belonging somewhere. The noun for 'membership' + linking-s + the noun for 'emotion.'",sSrc:"Verumius has finally found a sense of belonging in Berlin."},
{type:"teach",trg:"doch",src:"(particle: contradicts/insists)",pos:"part",gender:null,note:"Contradicts, reassures, or insists. 'Komm doch mit!'\n(Come along, won't you!). The most versatile particle.",example:"A: Ich kann das nicht.\nB: Doch, du kannst das!\nA: Komm doch mit!\nB: Na gut, ich komme doch mit.",exampleSrc:"A: I can't do that.\nB: Yes you can!\nA: Come along, won't you!\nB: All right, I'll come along after all.",funFact:"The most versatile German particle. Can mean 'after all,' 'but,' 'yes it is,' 'please do.' 'Doch' can be a one-word sentence answering a negative question with 'yes.' Untranslatable perfection."},
{type:"teach",trg:"mal",src:"(particle: softens requests)",pos:"part",gender:null,note:"From einmal (once). Makes requests casual and friendly.\n'Schau mal!' (Look!). Without mal, requests sound blunt.",example:"A: Schau mal, die Pflanzen!\nB: Oh, die sind sch\u00f6n.\nA: Komm mal her, ich zeige dir was.\nB: Moment, ich komme gleich mal.",exampleSrc:"A: Look, the plants!\nB: Oh, they are beautiful.\nA: Come here, I'll show you something.\nB: Just a moment, I'll come right over.",funFact:"Without mal, German requests sound military. With it, they sound human. 'Schau mal!' (Look!). 'Hoer mal!' (Listen!). Shortened from 'einmal' (once), it is the friendliness particle."},
{type:"teach",trg:"eben",src:"(particle: accepts unchangeable reality)",pos:"part",gender:null,note:"Signals resignation or acceptance. 'Das ist eben so.'\n(That's just the way it is.) No point arguing.",example:"A: Warum regnet es immer in Berlin?\nB: Das ist eben so. Berliner Wetter.\nA: Dann muss man eben einen Schirm mitnehmen.\nB: Eben. So ist das Leben.",exampleSrc:"A: Why does it always rain in Berlin?\nB: That's just how it is. Berlin weather.\nA: Then one simply has to take an umbrella.\nB: Exactly. That's life.",funFact:"Eben as particle: 'Das ist eben so' (That's just the way it is). Calm resignation. Also means 'just now': 'Ich war eben dort' (I was just there). And 'flat/level': 'eine ebene Fl\u00e4che' (a flat surface). Three meanings."},
{type:"teach",trg:"halt",src:"(particle: Southern German for eben)",pos:"part",gender:null,note:"Southern German/Austrian equivalent of eben. More colloquial.\n'Das ist halt so.' (That's just how it is.)",example:"A: In Bayern sagt man halt statt eben.\nB: Ja, das ist halt so.\nA: Versteht man halt \u00fcberall?\nB: Ja, aber es klingt halt s\u00fcdlich.",exampleSrc:"A: In Bavaria they say halt instead of eben.\nB: Yes, that's just how it is.\nA: Is halt understood everywhere?\nB: Yes, but it sounds Southern.",funFact:"Southern German/Austrian equivalent of eben. More colloquial, warmer. Lukas would say halt, Dr. Yilmaz would say eben. Regional particles reveal where you learned your German."},
{type:"teach",trg:"wohl",src:"(particle: probability/concession)",pos:"part",gender:null,note:"Expresses probability or concession. 'Er wird wohl schon\nzu Hause sein.' (He is probably already home.)",example:"A: Wo ist Verumius?\nB: Er wird wohl schon in Berlin sein.\nA: Das mag wohl stimmen.\nB: Wohl. Ganz sicher bin ich mir nicht.",exampleSrc:"A: Where is Verumius?\nB: He is probably already in Berlin.\nA: That may well be true.\nB: Probably. I am not entirely sure.",funFact:"Wohl as particle hedges without committing. 'Er wird wohl kommen' (He will probably come). Also: 'Wohl oder \u00fcbel' (willy-nilly, like it or not). Wohl softens claims into probabilities."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"mal",src:"(particle: softens requests)"},{trg:"eben",src:"(particle: accepts unchangeable reality)"},{trg:"halt",src:"(particle: Southern German for eben)"},{trg:"wohl",src:"(particle: probability/concession)"}]},
{type:"teach",trg:"eigentlich",src:"(particle: qualifies/corrects)",pos:"part",gender:null,note:"Introduces the real truth behind appearances.\n'Eigentlich wollte ich bleiben.' (Actually, I wanted to stay.)",example:"A: Was machst du eigentlich hier?\nB: Eigentlich wollte ich nur kurz schauen.\nA: Eigentlich ist Berlin meine Heimat.\nB: Ja, das hast du eigentlich immer gewusst.",exampleSrc:"A: What are you actually doing here?\nB: Actually, I just wanted to have a quick look.\nA: Actually, Berlin is my home.\nB: Yes, you actually always knew that.",funFact:"'Eigentlich' introduces the real truth. 'Was willst du eigentlich?' (What do you actually want?). In questions it adds genuine curiosity. In statements it corrects: 'Eigentlich mag ich Berlin' (Actually, I like Berlin)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"denn",src:"(particle: warms up questions)",pos:"part",gender:null,note:"As particle (not conjunction): makes questions warmer.\n'Was machst du denn?' sounds friendlier than 'Was machst du?'",example:"A: Was machst du denn hier?\nB: Ich besuche denn mal Berlin.\nA: Wie geht es dir denn?\nB: Gut, danke. Und dir?",exampleSrc:"A: So what are you doing here?\nB: I am visiting Berlin.\nA: So how are you?\nB: Good, thanks. And you?",funFact:"Denn in questions adds interest and warmth. 'Was machst du denn?' vs 'Was machst du?' The first sounds curious, the second sounds like an interrogation. Denn humanizes questions."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Komm doch mit!' Was macht 'doch' in diesem Satz?",opts:["Es verneint die Aufforderung vollst\u00e4ndig","Es stellt eine direkte Frage an die Person","Es mildert und ermutigt die Einladung","Es dr\u00fcckt \u00dcberraschung \u00fcber etwas aus"],ans:"Es mildert und ermutigt die Einladung",hint:"'Doch' as a particle can insist, contradict, or encourage. Here in an imperative it softens the request and makes it inviting."}
]},
{id:"deu_r33l7b",title:"Jedes Wort eine Erinnerung (Teil 2)",icon:"\ud83d\udcdd",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Jedes Wort eine Erinnerung (continued)",desc:"Continue practicing the vocabulary from this topic.",goals:["Review and practice key words"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"schon",src:"(particle: reassures/concedes)",pos:"part",gender:null,note:"Reassures or concedes. 'Das wird schon klappen.'\n(It will work out, don't worry.)",example:"A: Ich habe Angst vor der Pr\u00fcfung.\nB: Das wird schon klappen.\nA: Du hast schon recht.\nB: Siehst du? Es wird schon gut.",exampleSrc:"A: I am afraid of the exam.\nB: It will work out, don't worry.\nA: You are right, I suppose.\nB: See? It will be fine.",funFact:"Schon as particle calms fears. 'Das wird schon' (It'll be fine). Also concedes: 'Du hast schon recht' (You're right, I suppose). Reassuring and slightly resigned at the same time."},
{type:"teach",trg:"blo\u00df",src:"(particle: intensifies warnings/questions)",pos:"part",gender:null,note:"Adds urgency or desperation. 'Mach das blo\u00df nicht!'\n(Whatever you do, don't do that!)",example:"A: Mach das blo\u00df nicht!\nB: Warum denn nicht?\nA: Was soll ich blo\u00df tun?\nB: Beruhige dich. Es wird schon klappen.",exampleSrc:"A: Whatever you do, don't do that!\nB: Why not?\nA: What on earth should I do?\nB: Calm down. It will work out.",funFact:"Blo\u00df as particle intensifies. 'Wo ist blo\u00df mein Schl\u00fcssel?' (Where on earth is my key?). 'Mach das blo\u00df nicht!' (Don't you dare!). Adds desperation or urgency. Also means 'merely': 'blo\u00df ein Kind' (merely a child)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"ruhig",src:"(particle: gives permission encouragingly)",pos:"part",gender:null,note:"Permission given calmly. 'Du kannst ruhig bleiben.'\n(You can go ahead and stay, it's fine.)",example:"A: Darf ich noch bleiben?\nB: Du kannst ruhig bleiben.\nA: Sag ruhig deine Meinung.\nB: Na gut. Ich finde Berlin wunderbar.",exampleSrc:"A: May I stay a bit longer?\nB: You can go ahead and stay.\nA: Feel free to say your opinion.\nB: All right. I find Berlin wonderful.",funFact:"Ruhig (calm/quiet) as particle: permission given calmly. 'Nimm ruhig noch ein St\u00fcck Kuchen' (Go ahead and take another piece of cake). The speaker is calm about it. Take it, no problem."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Seitdem er verwurzelt ist, empfindet er keine Angst vor der Zukunft und ist stolz auf seine Wahlheimat.' Welche drei Konstrukte?",opts:["nur Temporalsatz, kein weiteres Konstrukt","Temporalsatz + Nomen+Pr\u00e4p + Adj+Pr\u00e4p","nur Nomen+Pr\u00e4p ohne Temporalsatz","nur Adj+Pr\u00e4p und Nomen+Pr\u00e4p kombiniert"],ans:"Temporalsatz + Nomen+Pr\u00e4p + Adj+Pr\u00e4p",hint:"Three constructs in one sentence: a temporal connector, a noun paired with a fixed connector, and a describing word paired with a fixed connector."},
{type:"fb",s:"Der Wunsch {1} Geborgenheit begleitet jeden Menschen.",a:["nach"],opts:["nach","auf","vor","von"],hint:"'Wunsch' pairs with a directional preposition. You wish for something you do not yet have.",sSrc:"The wish for security accompanies every person."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Das ist ja wunderbar!' Was macht 'ja' in diesem Satz?",opts:["es dient als einfache Zustimmung ('ja, genau')","es stellt eine direkte Frage an den H\u00f6rer","es verneint den gesamten Satz vollst\u00e4ndig","es dr\u00fcckt \u00dcberraschung oder Betonung aus"],ans:"es dr\u00fcckt \u00dcberraschung oder Betonung aus",hint:"'Ja' as a modal particle signals the speaker's reaction. Not 'ja' as agreement, but 'oh/wow.'"},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"{1} er lange gesucht hatte, fand er endlich {2} in Berlin.",blanks:{"1":"Nachdem","2":"Zuflucht"},pool:["Nachdem","Zuflucht","Bevor","Sehnsucht","W\u00e4hrend","Geborgenheit"],hint:"A temporal conjunction indicating completed prior action plus a feminine noun from the pool describing what one finds after long searching. Consider which pool items fit both the grammar and the emotional meaning.",sSrc:"After he had searched for a long time, he finally found refuge in Berlin."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Sie ist neugierig auf die neue Stadt.' Warum Akkusativ nach auf?",opts:["auf verlangt in dieser Konstruktion immer Dativ","die korrekte Pr\u00e4position w\u00e4re hier von + Dativ","der Kasus spielt bei Adjektiven keine Rolle","neugierig auf verlangt Akkusativ (gerichtet auf)"],ans:"neugierig auf verlangt Akkusativ (gerichtet auf)",hint:"This adjective-preposition pair uses a two-way preposition. When the feeling is directed TOWARD something, which case does it take?"},
{type:"fb",s:"{1} er ankam, f\u00fchlte er sich zu Hause.",a:["Sobald"],opts:["Sobald","Nachdem","Bevor","Bis"],hint:"The moment he arrived. Immediate sequence. The fastest temporal connector.",sSrc:"As soon as he arrived, he felt at home."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"doch (Partikel)",src:"widerspricht/besteht (doch!)"},{trg:"mal (Partikel)",src:"mildert eine Bitte (schau mal)"},{trg:"ja (Partikel)",src:"signalisiert \u00dcberraschung (wow!)"},{trg:"eben (Partikel)",src:"akzeptiert Realit\u00e4t (ist halt so)"}]},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'schon'?",opts:["(particle: warms up questions)","sense of belonging","(particle: reassures/concedes)","(particle: contradicts/insists)"],ans:"(particle: reassures/concedes)",hint:"As a modal word (not 'already'), it softens and acknowledges something comfortingly: 'it will be fine'."},
{type:"fb",s:"Du kannst {1} bleiben.",a:["ruhig"],opts:["denn","mal","ruhig","das Versprechen"],hint:"As a modal particle (not 'quiet'), it grants permission: 'feel free to, go ahead and'.",sSrc:"You can go ahead and stay."},
{type:"mc",q:"Seine {blank} hilft ihm, sich in der Stadt zurechtzufinden.",opts:["Ortskenntnis","Verwandtschaft","Geborgenheit","Nostalgie"],ans:"Ortskenntnis",hint:"Knowledge of a specific place. Ort (place) + Kenntnis (knowledge). Knowing the local area well."},
{type:"fb",s:"Die ganze {1} kommt zu Weihnachten zusammen.",a:["Verwandtschaft"],opts:["Verwandtschaft","Nachbarschaft","Ortskenntnis","Geborgenheit"],hint:"All your relatives as a group. From 'verwandt' (related). The collective noun for family members.",sSrc:"The whole extended family comes together at Christmas."}
]},
{id:"deu_r33l8",title:"Willkommen zur\u00fcck",icon:"\ud83c\udf3f",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Willkommen zur\u00fcck",desc:"Verumius is home. Hildi watered the plants. All constructs, all vocabulary, the whole concept of Heimat in one final chapter.",goals:["Consolidate all Heimat vocabulary","Use all temporal, adjective, and noun-preposition constructs","Articulate what Heimat means"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"etwa",src:"(particle: challenges/approximates)",pos:"part",gender:null,note:"Two uses: questioning tone (really? don't tell me!) and\napproximation. 'Hast du etwa Angst?'",example:"A: Hast du etwa Angst?\nB: Nein, nat\u00fcrlich nicht.\nA: Das ist etwa drei Kilometer entfernt.\nB: Also nicht weit. Gehen wir zu Fu\u00df.",exampleSrc:"A: Are you perhaps afraid?\nB: No, of course not.\nA: That is approximately three kilometers away.\nB: So not far. Let's walk.",funFact:"Etwa as particle challenges: 'Hast du etwa Angst?' (Don't tell me you're afraid!). As adverb: 'etwa 50 Leute' (approximately 50 people). The same word questions and estimates."},
{type:"teach",trg:"nun mal",src:"(particle: that's simply how it is)",pos:"part",gender:null,note:"Nun (now) + mal (just). Double particle for double resignation.\nStronger than eben or halt.",example:"A: Warum muss ich Grammatik lernen?\nB: Das ist nun mal so. Ohne Grammatik kein Deutsch.\nA: Berlin ist nun mal meine Heimat.\nB: Und daran \u00e4ndert sich nichts.",exampleSrc:"A: Why do I have to learn grammar?\nB: That's simply how it is. No grammar, no German.\nA: Berlin is simply my home.\nB: And nothing will change that.",funFact:"Nun (now) + mal (just). Double particle for double resignation. 'Das ist nun mal so' is stronger than 'Das ist eben so.' There is truly nothing to be done, and everyone knows it."},
{type:"fb",s:"Hast du {1} Angst? Nein, nat\u00fcrlich nicht!",a:["etwa"],opts:["etwa","doch","mal","eben"],hint:"The particle that adds a challenging tone to a question: 'Don't tell me you are afraid!' It questions with surprise.",sSrc:"Are you perhaps afraid? No, of course not!"},
{type:"teach",trg:"durchaus",src:"absolutely, by all means",pos:"adv",gender:null,note:"Durch (through) + aus (out). Emphatic agreement.\n'Das ist durchaus m\u00f6glich.' (That is absolutely possible.)",example:"A: Ist Berlin eine sch\u00f6ne Stadt?\nB: Durchaus. Auf seine eigene Art.\nA: Kann man dort gl\u00fccklich werden?\nB: Durchaus. Viele Menschen sind es.",exampleSrc:"A: Is Berlin a beautiful city?\nB: Absolutely. In its own way.\nA: Can you become happy there?\nB: Absolutely. Many people are.",funFact:"Durch (through) + aus (out). All the way through. 'Durchaus nicht' (absolutely not). 'Durchaus m\u00f6glich' (absolutely possible). The word goes through-and-out, leaving no doubt."},
{type:"teach",trg:"ohnehin",src:"anyway, regardless",pos:"adv",gender:null,note:"Ohne (without) + hin (there). No matter what: the outcome was\nalready decided. A calm dismissal of alternatives.",example:"A: Soll ich mitfahren?\nB: Ich wollte ohnehin nach Berlin.\nA: Dann ist es ohnehin kein Umweg.\nB: Genau. Steig ein.",exampleSrc:"A: Should I come along?\nB: I was going to Berlin anyway.\nA: Then it is no detour anyway.\nB: Exactly. Get in.",funFact:"Ohne (without) + hin (there). 'Ich wollte ohnehin gehen' (I was going to leave anyway). The action happens regardless of what you say. Calmer and more formal than sowieso."},
{type:"teach",trg:"sowieso",src:"anyway, in any case",pos:"adv",gender:null,note:"So + wie + so. More colloquial than ohnehin. Both mean the\nsame: the action happens regardless.",example:"A: Brauchst du einen Regenschirm?\nB: Nein, ich werde sowieso nass.\nA: Soll ich anrufen?\nB: Nicht n\u00f6tig. Ich komme sowieso vorbei.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you need an umbrella?\nB: No, I will get wet anyway.\nA: Should I call?\nB: Not necessary. I am coming by anyway.",funFact:"So + wie + so. The most casual way to say 'anyway.' 'Ich wollte sowieso...' (I was going to anyway). More colloquial than ohnehin. Both dismiss alternatives, but sowieso does it with a shrug."},
{type:"teach",trg:"zur\u00fcck",src:"back, return",pos:"adv",gender:null,note:"Zu (to) + r\u00fcck (back). Both adverb and prefix.\nzur\u00fcckkommen, zur\u00fcckgehen, zur\u00fcckdenken.",example:"A: Willkommen zur\u00fcck in Berlin!\nB: Danke. Es f\u00fchlt sich gut an, zur\u00fcck zu sein.\nA: Wann bist du zur\u00fcckgekommen?\nB: Gestern Abend.",exampleSrc:"A: Welcome back to Berlin!\nB: Thanks. It feels good to be back.\nA: When did you come back?\nB: Yesterday evening.",funFact:"Zu (to) + r\u00fcck (back). The direction of return. As prefix it creates dozens of verbs: zur\u00fcckkommen (come back), zur\u00fcckgehen (go back), zur\u00fcckdenken (think back), zur\u00fccklassen (leave behind)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"Abschied nehmen",src:"to say goodbye",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Abschied (farewell) + nehmen (to take). You take the farewell.\nActive: you choose to let go.",example:"A: Es ist Zeit, Abschied zu nehmen.\nB: Ja, aber Abschied ist nicht f\u00fcr immer.\nA: Hast du Abschied von der Heimat genommen?\nB: Ja, aber sie bleibt in meinem Herzen.",exampleSrc:"A: It is time to say goodbye.\nB: Yes, but goodbye is not forever.\nA: Did you say goodbye to your homeland?\nB: Yes, but it remains in my heart.",funFact:"Abschied (farewell) + nehmen (to take). 'Abschied nehmen von' + Dativ. You actively take the farewell. Not passive: you choose to let go. Every German departure deserves a proper Abschied."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"ohnehin",src:"anyway, regardless"},{trg:"sowieso",src:"anyway, in any case"},{trg:"zur\u00fcck",src:"back, return"},{trg:"Abschied nehmen",src:"to say goodbye"}]},
{type:"teach",trg:"fortziehen",src:"to move away",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Fort (away) + ziehen (to pull/move). Separable: 'Er zog fort.'\nPulling yourself away from where you are.",example:"A: Wann bist du von zu Hause fortgezogen?\nB: Mit achtzehn. Nach Berlin.\nA: Viele junge Leute ziehen fort.\nB: Ja, in die gro\u00dfe Stadt.",exampleSrc:"A: When did you move away from home?\nB: At eighteen. To Berlin.\nA: Many young people move away.\nB: Yes, to the big city.",funFact:"Fort (away) + ziehen (to pull/move). Separable. Perfect with sein: 'Er ist fortgezogen.' Fort implies distance: not just leaving but going far. 'Fortziehen und nie zur\u00fcckkommen' (to move away and never come back)."},
{type:"mc",q:"Ich wollte ohnehin nach Berlin fahren. Was bedeutet 'ohnehin'?",opts:["Auf keinen Fall, niemals","Sowieso, unabh\u00e4ngig davon","So schnell wie m\u00f6glich","Zum ersten Mal"],ans:"Sowieso, unabh\u00e4ngig davon",hint:"Ohne (without) + hin (there). The outcome was already decided regardless of what anyone says. A more formal word meaning 'regardless'."},
{type:"mc",q:"Das ist {blank} moeglich, wenn alle zusammenarbeiten.",opts:["durchaus","ohnehin","ruhig","etwa"],ans:"durchaus",hint:"An adverb meaning 'absolutely' or 'by all means.' Expresses that something is entirely possible."}
]},
{id:"deu_r33l8b",title:"Willkommen zur\u00fcck (Teil 2)",icon:"\ud83c\udf3f",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Willkommen zur\u00fcck (continued)",desc:"Continue practicing the vocabulary from this topic.",goals:["Review and practice key words"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"geh\u00f6ren",src:"to belong",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Ge- + h\u00f6ren (to hear/belong). Not separable.\n'Ich geh\u00f6re hierher.' (I belong here.)",example:"A: Geh\u00f6rst du nach Berlin?\nB: Ja, ich geh\u00f6re hierher.\nA: Wem geh\u00f6rt dieses Buch?\nB: Das geh\u00f6rt mir.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you belong in Berlin?\nB: Yes, I belong here.\nA: Who does this book belong to?\nB: That belongs to me.",funFact:"Ge- + h\u00f6ren (to hear). Two meanings: 'Ich geh\u00f6re hierher' (I belong here) and 'Das geh\u00f6rt mir' (That belongs to me). One of the deepest verbs in the Heimat vocabulary. Belonging is hearing your place."},
{type:"teach",trg:"nachtrauern",src:"to mourn (something past)",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Nach (after) + trauern (to mourn). Separable. Mourning after\nsomething that has moved away.",example:"A: Trauerst du der Vergangenheit nach?\nB: Manchmal. Aber nicht zu lange.\nA: Man sollte nicht der alten Zeit nachtrauern.\nB: Stimmt. Die Zukunft wartet.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you mourn the past?\nB: Sometimes. But not for too long.\nA: One should not mourn the old times.\nB: True. The future awaits.",funFact:"Nach (after) + trauern (to mourn). Separable: 'Er trauert der alten Zeit nach.' The nach implies the object has already moved away. You mourn after what is gone. Healthier than clinging."},
{type:"teach",trg:"zur\u00fcckkehren",src:"to return",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Zur\u00fcck (back) + kehren (to turn). Not separable.\nUses sein: 'Er ist zur\u00fcckgekehrt.'",example:"A: Wann kehrst du zur\u00fcck?\nB: N\u00e4chste Woche. Ich kehre nach Berlin zur\u00fcck.\nA: Er ist gestern zur\u00fcckgekehrt.\nB: Endlich. Wir haben ihn vermisst.",exampleSrc:"A: When are you returning?\nB: Next week. I am returning to Berlin.\nA: He returned yesterday.\nB: Finally. We missed him.",funFact:"Zur\u00fcck (back) + kehren (to turn). Separable despite appearances: 'Er kehrt zur\u00fcck.' Perfect with sein: 'Er ist zur\u00fcckgekehrt.' Synonym of r\u00fcckkehren. Turning back to where you started."},
{type:"teach",trg:"zur\u00fccklassen",src:"to leave behind",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Zur\u00fcck + lassen (to let/leave). Separable: 'Er lie\u00df alles zur\u00fcck.'\nWhat you choose not to bring with you.",example:"A: Was hast du zur\u00fcckgelassen?\nB: Die Vergangenheit. Und ein paar alte Fotos.\nA: Manche Dinge muss man zur\u00fccklassen.\nB: Ja, nur so kann man vorw\u00e4rtsgehen.",exampleSrc:"A: What did you leave behind?\nB: The past. And a few old photos.\nA: Some things you have to leave behind.\nB: Yes, only then can you move forward.",funFact:"Zur\u00fcck + lassen (to let/leave). Separable. Strong verb: zur\u00fccklassen/lie\u00df zur\u00fcck/zur\u00fcckgelassen. What you choose not to bring with you. 'Alles zur\u00fccklassen' (to leave everything behind) is the hardest kind of Aufbruch."},
{type:"teach",trg:"zusammenhalten",src:"to stick together",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Zusammen (together) + halten (to hold). Separable.\nThe verb behind Zusammenhalt.",example:"A: Familien m\u00fcssen zusammenhalten.\nB: Ja, in guten und in schlechten Zeiten.\nA: Die Nachbarschaft h\u00e4lt zusammen.\nB: Das ist echte Gemeinschaft.",exampleSrc:"A: Families must stick together.\nB: Yes, in good times and bad.\nA: The neighborhood sticks together.\nB: That is real community.",funFact:"Zusammen (together) + halten (to hold). Separable. Strong verb: zusammenhalten/hielt zusammen/zusammengehalten. The verb behind Zusammenhalt. What keeps a group unified when things get difficult."},
{type:"fb",s:"Familien m\u00fcssen {1}, besonders in schweren Zeiten.",a:["zusammenhalten"],opts:["zur\u00fccklassen","nachtrauern","zusammenhalten","fortziehen"],hint:"The separable verb meaning to stick together. Zusammen (together) + halten (to hold). What keeps a group unified.",sSrc:"Families must stick together, especially in difficult times."},
{type:"teach",trg:"entwurzeln",src:"to uproot",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Ent- (un-/de-) + Wurzel (root) + -n. The opposite of verwurzeln.\nTearing roots out. What migration does before new roots grow.",example:"A: Migration kann Menschen entwurzeln.\nB: Ja, aber neue Wurzeln k\u00f6nnen wachsen.\nA: F\u00fchlst du dich entwurzelt?\nB: Nicht mehr. Berlin hat mich verwurzelt.",exampleSrc:"A: Migration can uproot people.\nB: Yes, but new roots can grow.\nA: Do you feel uprooted?\nB: Not anymore. Berlin rooted me.",funFact:"Ent- (un-/de-) + Wurzel (root) + -n. The opposite of verwurzeln. Tearing roots out. 'Entwurzelte Menschen' (uprooted people). Migration uproots before new roots can grow. The ent- prefix reverses the process."},
{type:"teach",trg:"pflegen",src:"to care for, to cultivate",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"To nurture, maintain, cultivate. 'Freundschaften pflegen'\n(to cultivate friendships). The nurturing verb.",example:"A: Pflegst du deine Freundschaften?\nB: Ja, das ist mir wichtig.\nA: Hildi pflegt seine Pflanzen.\nB: Und seine Freundschaft. Ohne dass er es merkt.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you cultivate your friendships?\nB: Yes, that is important to me.\nA: Hildi tends to his plants.\nB: And his friendship. Without him noticing.",funFact:"'Freundschaften pflegen' (to cultivate friendships). 'Traditionen pflegen' (to maintain traditions). 'Kranke pflegen' (to care for the sick). The nurturing verb. What Hildi did for Verumius's plants."},
{type:"teach",trg:"pr\u00e4gen",src:"to shape, to stamp",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"To coin, to stamp, to shape. 'Die Erfahrung hat mich gepr\u00e4gt.'\nWhat your Heimat does to you.",example:"A: Was hat dich am meisten gepr\u00e4gt?\nB: Die zwei Jahre in Berlin.\nA: Orte pr\u00e4gen Menschen.\nB: Und Menschen pr\u00e4gen Orte.",exampleSrc:"A: What shaped you the most?\nB: The two years in Berlin.\nA: Places shape people.\nB: And people shape places.",funFact:"'Pr\u00e4gen' originally means to stamp coins. What your Heimat does to you: it stamps itself into your identity. 'Gepr\u00e4gt von der Erfahrung' (shaped by the experience). The stamp is permanent."},
{type:"tip",title:"Heimat: Das un\u00fcbersetzbare Wort",text:"Heimat has no exact English equivalent. It is more than 'home' (Zuhause), more than 'homeland' (Vaterland), more than 'origin' (Herkunft).\n\nHeimat is the place where your soul finds Geborgenheit. It can be a city, a smell, a language, a person.\n\nVerumius discovered that Heimat can shift: from where you grew up to where you arrived.\n\nNachdem er \u00fcberall gesucht hatte, fand er die Heimat dort, wo man ihn aufnahm.\n\n'Heimat ist kein Ort. Heimat ist ein Gef\u00fchl.'",deepDive:{title:"Heimat: The untranslatable word",text:"Heimat has no exact English equivalent. It is more than 'home' (which is Zuhause), more than 'homeland' (which is Vaterland), more than 'origin' (which is Herkunft). Heimat is where your Seele finds Geborgenheit. It can be a city, a smell, a language, a person. Verumius discovered that Heimat can shift: from where you grew up to where you grew into yourself."}},
{type:"mc",q:"'Nachdem er die Vergangenheit zur\u00fcckgelassen hatte, war er endlich zufrieden mit seiner Wahlheimat und empfand keine Sehnsucht nach dem Alten mehr.' Alle drei Konstrukte?",opts:["nur Temporalsatz, kein weiteres Konstrukt","nur Adj+Pr\u00e4p ohne jeglichen Temporalsatz","nur Nomen+Pr\u00e4p ohne Adj+Pr\u00e4p","Temporalsatz + Adj+Pr\u00e4p + Nomen+Pr\u00e4p"],ans:"Temporalsatz + Adj+Pr\u00e4p + Nomen+Pr\u00e4p",hint:"Count the structural types: a temporal clause with sequence rule, a describing-word-plus-connector combination, and a noun-plus-connector combination."},
{type:"fb",s:"{1} er in Berlin angekommen war, wusste er: das ist Heimat.",a:["Sobald"],opts:["Sobald","Nachdem","Bevor","Bis"],hint:"The moment of arrival equals the moment of knowing. Immediately. The fastest connector.",sSrc:"As soon as he had arrived in Berlin, he knew: this is home."},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"{1} er lange gesucht hatte, fand er Heimat. Er war {2} auf sein neues Leben und empfand tiefe Verbundenheit {3} Berlin.",blanks:{"1":"Nachdem","2":"stolz","3":"mit"},pool:["Nachdem","stolz","mit","Bevor","dankbar","von"],hint:"Three positions: a temporal conjunction indicating completed prior action, an adjective expressing a positive emotion about something achieved, and a preposition of accompaniment.",sSrc:"After he had searched for a long time, he found home. He was proud of his new life and felt deep connection with Berlin."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"Heimat",src:"home (emotional concept)"},{trg:"Sehnsucht",src:"deep longing"},{trg:"Geborgenheit",src:"sheltered safety"},{trg:"Verg\u00e4nglichkeit",src:"transience"}]},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'entwurzeln'?",opts:["to mourn (something past)","to say goodbye","to uproot","anyway, in any case"],ans:"to uproot",hint:"ent- (away from) + Wurzel (root). To tear something from its roots. The opposite of settling."},
{type:"fb",s:"Wie sagt man 'to care for, to cultivate' auf Deutsch? {1}",a:["pflegen"],opts:["nun mal","etwa","zur\\u00fcck","pflegen"],hint:"The verb for tending to something with care: a garden, a tradition, a sick person.",sSrc:"How do you say 'to care for, to cultivate' in German?"},
{type:"fb",s:"Diese Buecher {1} zur Pflichtlektüre an der Universitaet.",a:["gehören"],opts:["gehören","pflegen","prägen","kehren"],hint:"To belong. In this context, it means being part of something. Not separable.",sSrc:"These books belong to the required reading at the university."},
{type:"mc",q:"Nach zehn Jahren im Ausland will sie in ihre Heimat...?",opts:["zurückkehren","fortziehen","aufbrechen","entwurzeln"],ans:"zurückkehren",hint:"To return to where you came from. Zurück (back) + kehren (to turn/sweep). The journey home."},
{type:"fb",s:"Die Erfahrungen im Ausland haben ihn stark {1}.",a:["geprägt"],opts:["geprägt","entwurzelt","verwurzelt","gepflegt"],hint:"To shape or form someone's character. Past participle. The stamp that experience leaves on a person.",sSrc:"The experiences abroad shaped him profoundly."}
]}
]};

